{"title_page": "Robina Hope Mukisa", "text_new": "'''Hope Robina Mukisa''' (born 4 September 1991) is a [[Ugandan English|Ugandan]] female [[legislator]] and [[politician]]. She is the district woman representative for [[Namayingo District]] in the [[Parliament of Uganda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=271|title=Parliament of Uganda members of the 10th parliament|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of uganda|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>. She joined Parliament in 2016 on the [[National Resistance Movement|national resistance movement]] party (NRM) ticket,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrm.ug/organ/nrm-parliamentary-caucus|title=NRM parliamentary caucus|last=|first=|date=|website=NATIONAL RESISTANCE MOVEMENT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> the party in political leadership in Uganda under the chairmanship of [[Yoweri Museveni|Yoweri Kaguta Museveni]], the president of the Republic of Uganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1512423/museveni-summons-nrm-leaders-national-conference|title=Museveni summons NRM leaders for national conference|last=Charles|first=Etukuri|date=2019-12-20|website=New vision|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nMukisa attended St. Michael High School Mukono where she sat her [[Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education]] (UACE) in 2010. She thereafter attended [[Makerere University]] and graduated with a bachelor's degree in [[commerce]] (BCOM) in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=271|title=Mukisa Robina Hope education background|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of Uganda|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMukisa is a member of [[Parliament of Uganda]] representing the people of Namayingo district as a district woman representative, a position she has held since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_members_of_the_tenth_Parliament_of_Uganda|title=List of members of the tenth parliament of uganda|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> In parliament, she serves on the Committee on Tourism Trade and Industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parliamentwatch.ug/committee/committee-on-tourism-trade-and-industry/|title=Committee on tourism trade and industry|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament watch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She is also a member of the Uganda Women Parliamentary Association (UWOPA), where she serves on the \"succession act\" round table committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uwopa.or.ug/page/uwopa-round-table-committees|title=UWOPA round table committees|last=|first=|date=|website=Uganda Women parliamentary Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "'''Hope Robina Mukisa'''(born 4 September 1991) is a [[Ugandan English|Ugandan]] female [[legislator]] and [[politician]]. She is the district woman representative for [[Namayingo District]] in the [[Parliament of Uganda]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=271|title=Parliament of Uganda members of the 10th parliament|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of uganda|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>. She joined Parliament in 2016 on the [[National Resistance Movement|national resistance movement]] party (NRM) ticket,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nrm.ug/organ/nrm-parliamentary-caucus|title=NRM parliamentary caucus|last=|first=|date=|website=NATIONAL RESISTANCE MOVEMENT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> the party in political leadership in Uganda under the chairmanship of [[Yoweri Museveni|Yoweri Kaguta Museveni]], the president of the Republic of Uganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1512423/museveni-summons-nrm-leaders-national-conference|title=Museveni summons NRM leaders for national conference|last=Charles|first=Etukuri|date=2019-12-20|website=New vision|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nMukisa attended St. Michael High School Mukono where she sat her [[Uganda Advanced Certificate of Education]] (UACE) in 2010. She thereafter attended [[Makerere University]] and graduated with a bachelor's degree in [[commerce]] (BCOM) in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.go.ug/mp_database/profile.php?mid=271|title=Mukisa Robina Hope education background|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament of Uganda|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMukisa is a member of [[Parliament of Uganda]] representing the people of Namayingo district as a district woman representative, a position she has held since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_members_of_the_tenth_Parliament_of_Uganda|title=List of members of the tenth parliament of uganda|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> In parliament, she serves on the Committee on Tourism Trade and Industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parliamentwatch.ug/committee/committee-on-tourism-trade-and-industry/|title=Committee on tourism trade and industry|last=|first=|date=|website=Parliament watch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> She is also a member of the Uganda Women Parliamentary Association (UWOPA), where she serves on the \"succession act\" round table committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uwopa.or.ug/page/uwopa-round-table-committees|title=UWOPA round table committees|last=|first=|date=|website=Uganda Women parliamentary Association|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "David notMD", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robina_Hope_Mukisa"}
{"title_page": "Wet wipe", "text_new": "{{short description|A small moistened piece of paper or cloth}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2011}}\n[[File:Erfrischungstuch.jpg|thumb|An individually-wrapped wet wipe]]\n[[File:Wet wipes on a shelf.jpg|thumb|Wet wipes on a shelf]]\nA '''wet wipe''', also known as a '''wet towel''' or a '''moist towelette''', or a '''baby wipe''' in specific circumstances, is a small moistened piece of [[plastic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m0006347/war-on-plastic-with-hugh-and-anita-series-1-episode-2|title=War on Plastic with Hugh and Anita ||date=18 June 2019|website=the BBC}}</ref> or [[cloth]] that often comes folded and individually wrapped for [[convenience]]. Wet wipes are used for cleaning purposes like [[personal hygiene]] and [[household cleaning]].\n\n==Invention==\nAmerican Arthur Julius is seen as the inventor of the wet wipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/history/wet-nap-introduced-8cfcbfd823119534|title=When was the Wet-Nap introduced?|publisher=}}</ref> Julius worked in the [[cosmetics]] industry and in 1957, adjusted a soap portioning machine, putting it in a loft in [[Manhattan]]. Julius trademarked the name Wet-Nap in 1958, a name for the product that is still being used. After fine tuning his newfangled hand-cleaning aid together with a mechanic, he unveiled his invention at the 1960 National Restaurant Show in Chicago and in 1963 started selling Wet-Nap products to [[Colonel Sanders|Colonel Harland Sanders]] to be distributed to customers of [[KFC|Kentucky Fried Chicken]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eater.com/2016/6/17/11936294/wet-nap-inventor|title=A Brief History of the Wet-Nap, Barbecue Sauce's Worst Nightmare|first=Hillary|last=Dixler|date=17 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:\u0410\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0430\u043b\u0444\u0435\u0442\u043a\u0438.jpg|thumb|A wet wipe dispenser]]\n\nNinety percent of wet wipes on the market are produced from [[nonwoven fabric]]s made of [[polyester]] or [[polypropylene]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pajda |first1=Aleksandra |title=Did You Know Wet Wipes Are Made with Plastic? This Is Why the UK Wants Them Banned |url=http://www.onegreenplanet.org/news/wet-wipes-made-plastic-uk-wants-banned/ |publisher=One Green Planet |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe material is moistened with water or other liquids (e.g., [[isopropyl alcohol]]) depending on the applications. The material may be treated with softeners, lotions, or perfume to adjust the tactile and olfactory properties. Preservatives such as [[methylisothiazolinone]] are used to prevent bacterial or fungal growth in the package. The finished wet wipes are folded and put in pocket size package or a box dispenser.\n\n==Uses==\nWet wipes can serve a number of personal and household purposes.<ref>Rockline, [https://www.rockline.co.uk/products/ Product line</ref>  Although marketed primarily for wiping infants' bottoms in diaper changing, it is not uncommon for consumers to also use the product to clean floors, toilet seats, and other surfaces around the home. Parents also use wet wipes, or as they are called for baby care, baby wipes, for wiping up baby vomit and to clean babies' hands and faces. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/covers/2002-07-11-wipes.htm|title=More consumers whip out wet wipes|last=Horovitz|first=Bruce|date=2002-07-11|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Baby wipes===\nBaby wipes are wet wipes used to cleanse the sensitive skin of infants. These are saturated with solutions anywhere from gentle cleansing ingredients to alcohol-based \"cleaners\". Baby wipes are typically different pack counts (ranging up to 80 or more sheets per pack), and come with dispensing mechanisms. The origin of baby wipes most likely came in the mid-1950s as more people were travelling and needed a way to clean up on the go. One of the first companies to produce these was a company called Nice-Pak. They made napkin sized paper cloth saturated with a scented skin cleanser. Rockline Industries of [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] (which has a large part of the [[private label]] wipe market in several segments) went on to be the first to innovate the first baby wipe refill pack and pop-up packs which have become common in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockline.co.uk|title=Rockline Europe - Leading European Wet Wipes Manufacturer|website=Rockline Europe}}</ref>\n\nThe first wet-wipe products specifically marketed as baby wipes, such as [[Kimberly-Clark]]'s Huggies wipes and [[Procter & Gamble]]'s Pampers wipes, appeared on the market in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kimberly-clark.com/Timeline.aspx|author=|date= |title=Historical Journey: An Interactive Timeline |publisher=Kimberly-Clark |accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref> As the technology to produce wipes matured and became more affordable, smaller brands began to appear.{{citation needed|date=November 2009}} By the 1990s, most super stores like Kmart and Wal-Mart had their own [[private label brand]] of wipes made by other manufacturers. After this period there was a boom in the industry and many local brands started manufacturing because of low [[entry barrier]]s.\n\nMany green-minded parents, or those looking to save extra money, use washable baby wipes, typically small squares of material (such as cotton, bamboo or fleece) that can be pre-soaked ready to use, or wet as required. The cloths are wetted with either just water, commercial wipe solution or homemade solutions. Some parents prefer to use only water or their own homemade solutions as they can more directly control the ingredients used on the child\u2019s skin. Some parents feel that cloth wipes are more effective at removing solids from the skin than commercial one-use wipes because of their textured nature.\n\n===Personal hygiene===\nWet wipes are often included as part of a standard sealed [[cutlery]] package offered in restaurants or along with [[airline meal]]s.\n\nWet wipes began to be marketed as a luxury alternative to [[toilet paper]] by 2005 by companies such as [[Kimberly-Clark]] and [[Procter & Gamble]].<ref name=Atlantic>{{cite news|last1=Kessler|first1=Matt|title=Are Wet Wipes Wrecking the World's Sewers?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/10/are-wet-wipes-wrecking-the-worlds-sewers/504098/|accessdate=17 October 2016|work=The Atlantic|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> They are dispensed in the toilets of restaurants, service stations, doctors' offices, and other places with public use.\n\nWet wipes have also found a use among visitors to outdoor music festivals, particularly those who camp, as an alternative to communal showers. The wet wipes are a preferable option to the communal facilities, for which there are long queues.{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn Southeast Asia, wet wipes are often sold out of refrigerators to give the wipes a refreshingly cool effect.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===Cleansing pads===\nCleansing pads are fiber sponges which have been previously soaked with water, alcohol and other active ingredients for a specific intended use. They are ready to use hygiene products and they are simple and convenient solutions to dispose of dirt or other undesirable elements.\n\nThere are different type of cleansing pads offered by the beauty industry: make-up removing pads, anti-spot treatments and anti-acne pads that usually contain [[salicylic acid]], vitamins, menthol and other treatments).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acnemythsetc.com/are_cleansing_pads_good_for_acne.html|title=Acne Myths, Etc. - Are Cleansing Pads Good for Acne?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCleansing pads for preventing infection are usually saturated with alcohol and bundled in sterile packages. Hands and instruments may be disinfected with these pads while treating wounds. Disinfecting cleansing pads are often included in first aid kits for this purpose. Since the outbreak of [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1]] sales of individual impregnated wet wipes and gels in sachets and flowpacks have dramatically increased in the UK following the Government's advice to keep hands and surfaces clean to prevent the spread of germs.\n\n===Industrial wipes===\nPre-impregnated industrial-strength cleaning wipes with powerful cleaning fluid that cuts through the dirt as the high performance fabric absorbs the residue. Industrial wipes has the ability to clean a vast range of though substances from hands, tools and surfaces, including: grime, grease, oil- and water-based paints and coatings, adhesives, silicone and acrylic sealants, poly foam, epoxy, oil, tar and more.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wipermart.com/ |title=Supplier of Recycled Wiping Cotton rags, Cleaning rags with bag or box of rag wipers cloth |publisher=wipermart.com |language=en |access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>\n\n===Pain relief===\nThere are pain relief pads sopping with alcohol and [[benzocaine]]. These pads are good for treating minor scrapes, burns, and insect bites. They disinfect the injury and also ease pain and itching.\n\n===Pet care===\nToday one can find wet wipes for pet care, for example eye, ear, or dental cleansing pads (with [[boric acid]], [[potassium chloride]], [[zinc sulfate]], [[borax|sodium borate]]) for dogs, cats, horses, and birds.\n\n===Healthcare===\nMedical wet wipes are available for various applications. These include alcohol wet wipes, [[chlorhexidine]] wipes (for disinfection of surfaces and noninvasive medical devices) and sporicidal wipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medipal.co.uk/|title=Healthcare Wipes|date=30 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Medical wipes can be used to prevent the spread of [[pathogens]] such as [[norovirus]] and ''[[Clostridium difficile (bacteria)|Clostridium difficile]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palinternational.com/c-difficile-prevention-wipes.html |title=''Clostridium Difficile'' Prevention - ''C. Difficile'' Wipes |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141210055700/http://www.palinternational.com/c-difficile-prevention-wipes.html |archive-date=10 December 2014 |publisher=Pal International |access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on sewage systems==\nWater management companies ask people not to flush wet wipes down toilets, as their failure to break apart or dissolve in water can cause sewer blockages known as [[fatberg]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/dec/12/baby-wipes-93-percent-matter-causing-uk-sewer-blockages |title=Wet wipes make up 93% of matter causing UK sewer blockages |first=Matthew |last=Taylor |date=12 December 2017|website=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"ox2015\" />\n\nSince the mid-2000s, wet wipes such as baby wipes have become more common for use as an alternative to [[toilet paper]] in affluent countries, including the United States and the United Kingdom. This usage has in some cases been encouraged by manufacturers, who have labelled some wet wipe brands as \"flushable\". Wet wipes, when flushed down the toilet, have been reported to clog internal plumbing, [[septic system]]s and public sewer systems.<ref name=\"2013-one\">Shaver, Katherine (7 September 2013). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/flushable-personal-wipes-clogging-sewer-systems-utilities-say/2013/09/06/9efac4e6-157a-11e3-a2ec-b47e45e6f8ef_story.html 'Flushable' personal wipes clogging sewer systems, utilities say], ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref><ref name=\"may2009\">Stradling, Richard (31 May 2009). [http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2009281514_wipes31.html {{\"'}}Flushable' wipes blamed for clogging sewage lines\"], ''Seattle Times''</ref><ref name=ox2015>Regan, Alex (4 March 2015). [http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/11830693.Wet_wipes_caused_sewage_flood_in_garden/ \"Wet wipes caused sewage flood in garden\"], ''[[Oxford Mail]]''</ref> The tendency for [[fat]] and wet wipes to cling together allegedly encourages the growth of the problematic obstructions in sewers known as \"[[fatberg]]s\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Oxford 'out-of-control fatberg\u2019 threatens homes |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=1 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sewer repairs means 14 days of chaos ahead|access-date=8 April 2014 |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/11132490.Sewer_repairs_means_14_days_of_chaos_ahead/}}</ref> In addition, some brands of wipes contain alcohol, which can kill the bacteria and [[enzyme]]s responsible for breaking down solid waste in septic tanks.<ref name=\"sept2013\">Conte, Chris (12 Sept 2013). [http://www.newschannel5.com/story/23419415/flushable-wipes-creating-messy-septic-issues \"Flushable Wipes Creating Messy Septic Issues\"], Newschannel5.com</ref> In the late 2010s, other alternatives such as [[gel wipe]] had also come on to the market.<ref name=\"june2016\">Saat, Siim (25 June 2016). [https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/new-product-development-gel-wipe-satu-siim-saat \"New Product Development: GEL WIPE by SATU\"]. LinkedIn.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkart/2018/06/15/toilet-paper-gel-cleans-up-no-2-in-more-ways-than-one/ |title=Toilet Paper Gel Cleans Up No. 2 In More Ways Than One |magazine=[[Forbes]]|author=Kart, Jeff |date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014 a [[class action]] suit was filed in the [[U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Ohio]] against [[Target Corporation]], and Nice-Pak Products Inc. on behalf of consumers in Ohio who purchased Target-brand flushable wipes. The lawsuit alleged the retailer misled consumers by marking the packaging on its Up & Up brand wipes as flushable and safe for sewer and septic systems. The lawsuit also alleged that the products were a public health hazard because they clogged pumps at municipal waste-treatment facilities.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cellini |first=Lorenzo B. |title=Class Action Lawsuit Alleges That Target-Brand Flushable Wipes Are Not Suitable for Flushing and Can Clog Pipes and Damage Sewer and Septic Systems |url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/class-action-lawsuit-alleges-target-brand-flushable-wipes-are-not-suitable-flushing-|accessdate=19 April 2014 |journal=The National Law Review |date=18 April 2014 |author2=Tycko & Zavareei LLP}}</ref> Target and Nice-Pak agreed to [[settlement (law)|settle]] the case in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://topclassactions.com/lawsuit-settlements/lawsuit-news/845007-target-flushable-wipes-class-action-settlement/ |title=Target Flushable Wipes Class Action Settlement |date=7 May 2018 |publisher=topclassactions.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the city of [[Wyoming, Minnesota]], launched a class action suit against six companies, including Procter & Gamble, Kimberly-Clark, and Nice-Pak, alleging they were fraudulently promoting their products as \"flushable\".<ref name=Atlantic/> The city dropped the lawsuit in 2018 after concluding that the city had not experienced damage to its sewer systems or a rise in maintenance costs.<ref name=WyomingMinnDrop>{{cite web |url=https://www.innovationintextiles.com/city-of-wyoming-bows-out-of-flushable-wipes-lawsuit/ |title=City of Wyoming bows out of flushable wipes lawsuit |publisher=www.innovationintextiles.com}}</ref> Upon announcement of the withdrawal of the suit, an industry trade group representing the manufacturers of the wipes released a statement that disputed the claims that the products are harmful to sewer systems.\n{{quote|The withdrawal by the City of Wyoming and last year's settlement terms of the Perry litigation corroborate what years of testing and field collection studies have shown: flushable wipes are not causing municipal clogs or increased maintenance. To date, despite sensational headlines, no wastewater operator has offered any public evidence that its maintenance issues are impacted by wipes marketed as 'flushable' and passing the industry assessment tests.|David Rouse, president of INDA, Association of the Nonwoven Fabrics Industry (August 2018)<ref name=WyomingMinnDrop/>}}\n\nIn 2016, several British water companies including [[Wessex Water]] began a campaign advising consumers not to flush wet wipes down toilets because of added maintenance costs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Water companies declare war on 'flushable' wet wipes  |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/pa/article-3797782/Water-companies-declare-war-flushable-wet-wipes.html|accessdate=17 October 2016|work=Daily Mail |agency=Press Association |date=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the industry body [[Water UK]] announced a new standard for flushable wet wipes. Wipes will need to pass rigorous testing in order to gain a new and approved \"Fine to Flush\" logo. As of January 2019, only one product had been confirmed to meet the standard, although there were about seven others in the process of being tested.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-46835573</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anal cleansing]]\n* [[Gel wipe]]\n* [[Oshibori]], reusable Japanese wet hand towel\n* [[Washlet]], a mechanical alternative to wet wipes\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paper products}}\n\n[[Category:Personal hygiene products]]\n[[Category:Disinfectants]]\n[[Category:Paper products]]\n[[Category:Toilets]]\n[[Category:Babycare]]\n[[Category:Disposable products]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A small moistened piece of paper or cloth}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2011}}\n[[File:Erfrischungstuch.jpg|thumb|An individually-wrapped wet wipe]]\n[[File:Wet wipes on a shelf.jpg|thumb|Wet wipes on a shelf]]\nA '''wet wipe''', also known as a '''wet towel''' or a '''moist towelette''', or a '''baby wipe''' in specific circumstances, is a small moistened piece of [[plastic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m0006347/war-on-plastic-with-hugh-and-anita-series-1-episode-2|title=War on Plastic with Hugh and Anita ||date=18 June 2019|website=the BBC}}</ref> or [[cloth]] that often comes folded and individually wrapped for [[convenience]]. Wet wipes are used for cleaning purposes like [[personal hygiene]] and [[household cleaning]].\n\n==Invention==\nAmerican Arthur Julius is seen as the inventor of the wet wipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/history/wet-nap-introduced-8cfcbfd823119534|title=When was the Wet-Nap introduced?|publisher=}}</ref> Julius worked in the [[cosmetics]] industry and in 1957, adjusted a soap portioning machine, putting it in a loft in [[Manhattan]]. Julius trademarked the name Wet-Nap in 1958, a name for the product that is still being used. After fine tuning his newfangled hand-cleaning aid together with a mechanic, he unveiled his invention at the 1960 National Restaurant Show in Chicago and in 1963 started selling Wet-Nap products to Colonel Sanders for use in his [[KFC restaurant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eater.com/2016/6/17/11936294/wet-nap-inventor|title=A Brief History of the Wet-Nap, Barbecue Sauce's Worst Nightmare|first=Hillary|last=Dixler|date=17 June 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:\u0410\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0430\u043b\u0444\u0435\u0442\u043a\u0438.jpg|thumb|A wet wipe dispenser]]\n\nNinety percent of wet wipes on the market are produced from [[nonwoven fabric]]s made of [[polyester]] or [[polypropylene]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pajda |first1=Aleksandra |title=Did You Know Wet Wipes Are Made with Plastic? This Is Why the UK Wants Them Banned |url=http://www.onegreenplanet.org/news/wet-wipes-made-plastic-uk-wants-banned/ |publisher=One Green Planet |accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe material is moistened with water or other liquids (e.g., [[isopropyl alcohol]]) depending on the applications. The material may be treated with softeners, lotions, or perfume to adjust the tactile and olfactory properties. Preservatives such as [[methylisothiazolinone]] are used to prevent bacterial or fungal growth in the package. The finished wet wipes are folded and put in pocket size package or a box dispenser.\n\n==Uses==\nWet wipes can serve a number of personal and household purposes.<ref>Rockline, [https://www.rockline.co.uk/products/ Product line</ref>  Although marketed primarily for wiping infants' bottoms in diaper changing, it is not uncommon for consumers to also use the product to clean floors, toilet seats, and other surfaces around the home. Parents also use wet wipes, or as they are called for baby care, baby wipes, for wiping up baby vomit and to clean babies' hands and faces. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/covers/2002-07-11-wipes.htm|title=More consumers whip out wet wipes|last=Horovitz|first=Bruce|date=2002-07-11|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=16 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Baby wipes===\nBaby wipes are wet wipes used to cleanse the sensitive skin of infants. These are saturated with solutions anywhere from gentle cleansing ingredients to alcohol-based \"cleaners\". Baby wipes are typically different pack counts (ranging up to 80 or more sheets per pack), and come with dispensing mechanisms. The origin of baby wipes most likely came in the mid-1950s as more people were travelling and needed a way to clean up on the go. One of the first companies to produce these was a company called Nice-Pak. They made napkin sized paper cloth saturated with a scented skin cleanser. Rockline Industries of [[Sheboygan, Wisconsin]] (which has a large part of the [[private label]] wipe market in several segments) went on to be the first to innovate the first baby wipe refill pack and pop-up packs which have become common in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockline.co.uk|title=Rockline Europe - Leading European Wet Wipes Manufacturer|website=Rockline Europe}}</ref>\n\nThe first wet-wipe products specifically marketed as baby wipes, such as [[Kimberly-Clark]]'s Huggies wipes and [[Procter & Gamble]]'s Pampers wipes, appeared on the market in 1990.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kimberly-clark.com/Timeline.aspx|author=|date= |title=Historical Journey: An Interactive Timeline |publisher=Kimberly-Clark |accessdate=2013-09-10}}</ref> As the technology to produce wipes matured and became more affordable, smaller brands began to appear.{{citation needed|date=November 2009}} By the 1990s, most super stores like Kmart and Wal-Mart had their own [[private label brand]] of wipes made by other manufacturers. After this period there was a boom in the industry and many local brands started manufacturing because of low [[entry barrier]]s.\n\nMany green-minded parents, or those looking to save extra money, use washable baby wipes, typically small squares of material (such as cotton, bamboo or fleece) that can be pre-soaked ready to use, or wet as required. The cloths are wetted with either just water, commercial wipe solution or homemade solutions. Some parents prefer to use only water or their own homemade solutions as they can more directly control the ingredients used on the child\u2019s skin. Some parents feel that cloth wipes are more effective at removing solids from the skin than commercial one-use wipes because of their textured nature.\n\n===Personal hygiene===\nWet wipes are often included as part of a standard sealed [[cutlery]] package offered in restaurants or along with [[airline meal]]s.\n\nWet wipes began to be marketed as a luxury alternative to [[toilet paper]] by 2005 by companies such as [[Kimberly-Clark]] and [[Procter & Gamble]].<ref name=Atlantic>{{cite news|last1=Kessler|first1=Matt|title=Are Wet Wipes Wrecking the World's Sewers?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/10/are-wet-wipes-wrecking-the-worlds-sewers/504098/|accessdate=17 October 2016|work=The Atlantic|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> They are dispensed in the toilets of restaurants, service stations, doctors' offices, and other places with public use.\n\nWet wipes have also found a use among visitors to outdoor music festivals, particularly those who camp, as an alternative to communal showers. The wet wipes are a preferable option to the communal facilities, for which there are long queues.{{cn|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn Southeast Asia, wet wipes are often sold out of refrigerators to give the wipes a refreshingly cool effect.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===Cleansing pads===\nCleansing pads are fiber sponges which have been previously soaked with water, alcohol and other active ingredients for a specific intended use. They are ready to use hygiene products and they are simple and convenient solutions to dispose of dirt or other undesirable elements.\n\nThere are different type of cleansing pads offered by the beauty industry: make-up removing pads, anti-spot treatments and anti-acne pads that usually contain [[salicylic acid]], vitamins, menthol and other treatments).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acnemythsetc.com/are_cleansing_pads_good_for_acne.html|title=Acne Myths, Etc. - Are Cleansing Pads Good for Acne?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCleansing pads for preventing infection are usually saturated with alcohol and bundled in sterile packages. Hands and instruments may be disinfected with these pads while treating wounds. Disinfecting cleansing pads are often included in first aid kits for this purpose. Since the outbreak of [[2009 flu pandemic|H1N1]] sales of individual impregnated wet wipes and gels in sachets and flowpacks have dramatically increased in the UK following the Government's advice to keep hands and surfaces clean to prevent the spread of germs.\n\n===Industrial wipes===\nPre-impregnated industrial-strength cleaning wipes with powerful cleaning fluid that cuts through the dirt as the high performance fabric absorbs the residue. Industrial wipes has the ability to clean a vast range of though substances from hands, tools and surfaces, including: grime, grease, oil- and water-based paints and coatings, adhesives, silicone and acrylic sealants, poly foam, epoxy, oil, tar and more.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wipermart.com/ |title=Supplier of Recycled Wiping Cotton rags, Cleaning rags with bag or box of rag wipers cloth |publisher=wipermart.com |language=en |access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>\n\n===Pain relief===\nThere are pain relief pads sopping with alcohol and [[benzocaine]]. These pads are good for treating minor scrapes, burns, and insect bites. They disinfect the injury and also ease pain and itching.\n\n===Pet care===\nToday one can find wet wipes for pet care, for example eye, ear, or dental cleansing pads (with [[boric acid]], [[potassium chloride]], [[zinc sulfate]], [[borax|sodium borate]]) for dogs, cats, horses, and birds.\n\n===Healthcare===\nMedical wet wipes are available for various applications. These include alcohol wet wipes, [[chlorhexidine]] wipes (for disinfection of surfaces and noninvasive medical devices) and sporicidal wipes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medipal.co.uk/|title=Healthcare Wipes|date=30 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Medical wipes can be used to prevent the spread of [[pathogens]] such as [[norovirus]] and ''[[Clostridium difficile (bacteria)|Clostridium difficile]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.palinternational.com/c-difficile-prevention-wipes.html |title=''Clostridium Difficile'' Prevention - ''C. Difficile'' Wipes |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141210055700/http://www.palinternational.com/c-difficile-prevention-wipes.html |archive-date=10 December 2014 |publisher=Pal International |access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on sewage systems==\nWater management companies ask people not to flush wet wipes down toilets, as their failure to break apart or dissolve in water can cause sewer blockages known as [[fatberg]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/dec/12/baby-wipes-93-percent-matter-causing-uk-sewer-blockages |title=Wet wipes make up 93% of matter causing UK sewer blockages |first=Matthew |last=Taylor |date=12 December 2017|website=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"ox2015\" />\n\nSince the mid-2000s, wet wipes such as baby wipes have become more common for use as an alternative to [[toilet paper]] in affluent countries, including the United States and the United Kingdom. This usage has in some cases been encouraged by manufacturers, who have labelled some wet wipe brands as \"flushable\". Wet wipes, when flushed down the toilet, have been reported to clog internal plumbing, [[septic system]]s and public sewer systems.<ref name=\"2013-one\">Shaver, Katherine (7 September 2013). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/flushable-personal-wipes-clogging-sewer-systems-utilities-say/2013/09/06/9efac4e6-157a-11e3-a2ec-b47e45e6f8ef_story.html 'Flushable' personal wipes clogging sewer systems, utilities say], ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref><ref name=\"may2009\">Stradling, Richard (31 May 2009). [http://seattletimes.com/html/nationworld/2009281514_wipes31.html {{\"'}}Flushable' wipes blamed for clogging sewage lines\"], ''Seattle Times''</ref><ref name=ox2015>Regan, Alex (4 March 2015). [http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/11830693.Wet_wipes_caused_sewage_flood_in_garden/ \"Wet wipes caused sewage flood in garden\"], ''[[Oxford Mail]]''</ref> The tendency for [[fat]] and wet wipes to cling together allegedly encourages the growth of the problematic obstructions in sewers known as \"[[fatberg]]s\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Oxford 'out-of-control fatberg\u2019 threatens homes |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=1 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sewer repairs means 14 days of chaos ahead|access-date=8 April 2014 |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/11132490.Sewer_repairs_means_14_days_of_chaos_ahead/}}</ref> In addition, some brands of wipes contain alcohol, which can kill the bacteria and [[enzyme]]s responsible for breaking down solid waste in septic tanks.<ref name=\"sept2013\">Conte, Chris (12 Sept 2013). [http://www.newschannel5.com/story/23419415/flushable-wipes-creating-messy-septic-issues \"Flushable Wipes Creating Messy Septic Issues\"], Newschannel5.com</ref> In the late 2010s, other alternatives such as [[gel wipe]] had also come on to the market.<ref name=\"june2016\">Saat, Siim (25 June 2016). [https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/new-product-development-gel-wipe-satu-siim-saat \"New Product Development: GEL WIPE by SATU\"]. LinkedIn.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffkart/2018/06/15/toilet-paper-gel-cleans-up-no-2-in-more-ways-than-one/ |title=Toilet Paper Gel Cleans Up No. 2 In More Ways Than One |magazine=[[Forbes]]|author=Kart, Jeff |date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014 a [[class action]] suit was filed in the [[U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Ohio]] against [[Target Corporation]], and Nice-Pak Products Inc. on behalf of consumers in Ohio who purchased Target-brand flushable wipes. The lawsuit alleged the retailer misled consumers by marking the packaging on its Up & Up brand wipes as flushable and safe for sewer and septic systems. The lawsuit also alleged that the products were a public health hazard because they clogged pumps at municipal waste-treatment facilities.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cellini |first=Lorenzo B. |title=Class Action Lawsuit Alleges That Target-Brand Flushable Wipes Are Not Suitable for Flushing and Can Clog Pipes and Damage Sewer and Septic Systems |url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/class-action-lawsuit-alleges-target-brand-flushable-wipes-are-not-suitable-flushing-|accessdate=19 April 2014 |journal=The National Law Review |date=18 April 2014 |author2=Tycko & Zavareei LLP}}</ref> Target and Nice-Pak agreed to [[settlement (law)|settle]] the case in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://topclassactions.com/lawsuit-settlements/lawsuit-news/845007-target-flushable-wipes-class-action-settlement/ |title=Target Flushable Wipes Class Action Settlement |date=7 May 2018 |publisher=topclassactions.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the city of [[Wyoming, Minnesota]], launched a class action suit against six companies, including Procter & Gamble, Kimberly-Clark, and Nice-Pak, alleging they were fraudulently promoting their products as \"flushable\".<ref name=Atlantic/> The city dropped the lawsuit in 2018 after concluding that the city had not experienced damage to its sewer systems or a rise in maintenance costs.<ref name=WyomingMinnDrop>{{cite web |url=https://www.innovationintextiles.com/city-of-wyoming-bows-out-of-flushable-wipes-lawsuit/ |title=City of Wyoming bows out of flushable wipes lawsuit |publisher=www.innovationintextiles.com}}</ref> Upon announcement of the withdrawal of the suit, an industry trade group representing the manufacturers of the wipes released a statement that disputed the claims that the products are harmful to sewer systems.\n{{quote|The withdrawal by the City of Wyoming and last year's settlement terms of the Perry litigation corroborate what years of testing and field collection studies have shown: flushable wipes are not causing municipal clogs or increased maintenance. To date, despite sensational headlines, no wastewater operator has offered any public evidence that its maintenance issues are impacted by wipes marketed as 'flushable' and passing the industry assessment tests.|David Rouse, president of INDA, Association of the Nonwoven Fabrics Industry (August 2018)<ref name=WyomingMinnDrop/>}}\n\nIn 2016, several British water companies including [[Wessex Water]] began a campaign advising consumers not to flush wet wipes down toilets because of added maintenance costs.<ref>{{cite news |title=Water companies declare war on 'flushable' wet wipes  |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/pa/article-3797782/Water-companies-declare-war-flushable-wet-wipes.html|accessdate=17 October 2016|work=Daily Mail |agency=Press Association |date=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the industry body [[Water UK]] announced a new standard for flushable wet wipes. Wipes will need to pass rigorous testing in order to gain a new and approved \"Fine to Flush\" logo. As of January 2019, only one product had been confirmed to meet the standard, although there were about seven others in the process of being tested.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-46835573</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anal cleansing]]\n* [[Gel wipe]]\n* [[Oshibori]], reusable Japanese wet hand towel\n* [[Washlet]], a mechanical alternative to wet wipes\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Paper products}}\n\n[[Category:Personal hygiene products]]\n[[Category:Disinfectants]]\n[[Category:Paper products]]\n[[Category:Toilets]]\n[[Category:Babycare]]\n[[Category:Disposable products]]\n", "name_user": "Mrschimpf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvention", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wet_wipe"}
{"title_page": "Yala National Park", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Yala National Park\n| alt_name = {{lang|si|\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0dc0\u0db1\u0ddd\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dba}}<br/>{{lang|ta|\u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb2 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf \u0bb5\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd}}\n| iucn_category = II\n| map = Sri Lanka\n| relief = yes\n| map_width = 220\n| map_caption = Location of Yala National Park\n| photo = Yala Beach.jpg\n| photo_caption = Patanangala, a rock outcrop in the Yala beach\n| photo_alt = Sandy beach with a rocky outcrop in sea side\n| location = [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern]] and [[Uva Province|Uva]] Provinces, [[Sri Lanka]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hambantota]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|6|22|22|N|81|31|01|E|display=inline, title}}\n| area_km2 = 978.807\n| established = 1900 (Wildlife sanctuary)<br/> 1938 (National park)\n| visitation_num =\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[Department of Wildlife Conservation (Sri Lanka)|Department of Wildlife Conservation]]\n| website ={{url|www.yalasrilanka.lk}}\n}}\n\n'''Yala (\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd) National Park''' is the most visited and second largest [[national park]] in [[Sri Lanka]], bordering the [[Indian Ocean]]. The park consists of five blocks, two of which are now open to the public, and also adjoining parks. The blocks have individual names such as, '''Ruhuna National Park''' (Block 1), and [[Kumana National Park]] or 'Yala East' for the adjoining area. It is situated in the southeast region of the country, and lies in [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern Province]] and [[Uva Province]]. The park covers {{convert|979|km2|mi2}} and is located about {{convert|300|km|mi}} from [[Colombo]]. Yala was designated as a [[Wildlife refuge|wildlife sanctuary]] in 1900, and, along with [[Wilpattu National Park|Wilpattu]] was one of the first two national parks in Sri Lanka, having been designated in 1938. The park is best known for its variety of wild animals. It is important for the conservation of [[Sri Lankan elephant]]s, [[Sri Lankan leopard]]s and aquatic birds.\n\nThere are six national parks and three wildlife sanctuaries in the vicinity of Yala. Among the largest is [[Lunugamvehera National Park]]. The park is situated in the [[Geography of Sri Lanka#Climate|dry semi-arid climatic region]] and rain is received mainly during the [[monsoon|northeast monsoon]]. Yala hosts a variety of [[ecosystem]]s ranging from moist monsoon forests to freshwater and marine [[wetland]]s. It is one of the 70 [[Important Bird Area]]s (IBAs) in Sri Lanka. Yala harbours 215 bird species including six endemic species of Sri Lanka. The number of [[mammal]]s that has been recorded from the park is 44, and it has one of the highest [[leopard]] densities in the world.\n\nThe area around Yala has hosted several ancient civilizations. Two important pilgrim sites, '''Sithulpahuwa''' and '''Magul Vihara''', are situated within the park. The [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]] caused severe damage on the Yala National Park and 250 people died in its vicinity. The number of visitors has been on the rise since 2009, after the security situation in the park improved.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1560 Spanish cartographer Cipriano Sanchez noted Yala in his map \"is abandoned for 300 years due to insalubrious conditions.\"<ref name=\"Brohier\" >{{cite book |last=Brohier |first=R. L. |title=Brohier dutu Lankawa |trans-title=The Ceylon that Brohier seen |editor=Hewawasam, Abhaya |publisher=Sooriya Publishers |year=2001 |edition=2nd |isbn=978-955-9348-63-4 |pages=312\u2013320 |language=Sinhala}}</ref> Chief Justice Sir [[Alexander Johnston (1775\u20131849)|Alexander Johnston]] wrote a detailed account on Yala in 1806 after travelling from [[Trincomalee]] to [[Hambantota]]. On March 23, 1900 the government proclaimed Yala and [[Wilpattu National Park|Wilpattu]] reserves under the Forest Ordinance.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\">{{cite book |last=Senaratna |first=P.M. |title=Sri Lankawe Jathika Vanodhyana |publisher=Sarasavi Publishers |year=2009 |edition=2nd |pages=22\u201369 |chapter=Yala |isbn=978-955-573-346-5 |language=Sinhala}}</ref> Initially the extent of the reserve was {{convert|389|km2|mi2}} between the Menik  and Kumbukkan Rivers. At that time the reserve did not bear the name Yala. The Game Protection Society (now the Wildlife and Nature Protection Society) was instrumental in establishing the reserve. The forest area between Palatupana and Yala was declared a hunting site reserved only for the resident sportsmen.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> [[Henry Engelbrecht]] was appointed as the first park warden.\n\n[[File:Yala Map.jpg|thumb|350px|Map of the National Park]]\nOn 1 March 1938, Yala became a national park when the Flora and Fauna Protection Ordinance was passed into law by [[Don Stephen Senanayake|D. S. Senanayake]], the minister of agriculture. The park consists of five blocks.<ref name=\"iwmi\">{{cite web|url=http://dw.iwmi.org/wetland_profile/Ruhuna.asp|title=Ruhuna National Park|work=Sri Lanka Wetlands Information and Database|publisher=[[International Water Management Institute]]|accessdate=15 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726201837/http://dw.iwmi.org/wetland_profile/Ruhuna.asp|archivedate=26 July 2011}}</ref> Subsequently, four other blocks were incorporated to the park. There are six national parks and three wildlife sanctuaries in the vicinity of Yala. [[Kumana National Park]], Yala Strict Nature Reserve and Kataragama, Katagamuwa, and Nimalawa sanctuaries are continuous with the park.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Block\n! Extent\n! Date added to the park\n|-\n| Block I\n| {{convert|14,101|ha|mi2}}\n| 1938\n|-\n| Block II\n| {{convert|9,931|ha|mi2}}\n| 1954\n|-\n| Block III\n| {{convert|40,775|ha|mi2}}\n| 1967\n|-\n| Block IV\n| {{convert|26,418|ha|mi2}}\n| 1969\n|-\n| Block V\n| {{convert|6,656|ha|mi2}}\n| 1973\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" | Source: ''Sri Lanka Wetlands Information and Database''<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n|}\n\n== Physical features ==\n[[File:Yalapond.jpg|thumb|alt=A dead tree by a body of water|Surface water becomes critical in the dry season]]\n\nThe Yala area is mostly composed of [[metamorphic rock]] belonging to the [[Precambrian]] era and classified into two series, Vijayan series and Highland series. Reddish brown soil and low [[Humus|humic]] grey soil are prominent among six [[soil type]]s. Yala is situated in the lowest [[peneplain]] of Sri Lanka, which extends from Trincomalee to Hambantota.  Topographically the area is a flat and mildly undulating plain that runs to the coast with elevation is {{convert|30|m|ft}} close to the coast while rising in the interior to {{convert|100|-|125|m|ft}}. The national park is situated in the [[Geography of Sri Lanka#Climate|dry semi-arid climatic region]] and rain is received mainly during the [[monsoon|northeast monsoon]]. The mean annual rainfall ranges between {{convert|500|-|775|mm|in}} while the mean temperature ranges between {{convert|26.4|C|F}} in January to {{convert|30|C|F}} in April. It is  windier in Yala, during the southwest monsoon compared to the wind during the northeast monsoon with wind speeds from {{convert|23|km/h|mi/h}} to {{convert|15|km/h|mi/h}}.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\nWater is abundant after the northeast monsoon, but during the dry season surface water becomes an important factor. The bodies of surface water appear in the forms of [[stream]]s, tanks, waterholes, rock pools, and [[lagoon]]s. Waterholes occur in low lying places while rock pools of varying size are capable of containing water year-round, and are hence an important source of water for elephants. For many water birds and [[Water Buffalo|water buffaloes]] natural waterholes are ideal habitats. Such reservoirs are largely concentrated to the Block I followed by Block II. Several tanks  are there including, Maha Seelawa, Buthawa, Uraniya, and Pilinnawa tanks.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> Many rivers and streams flow in a southeasterly direction, originating in the highlands of adjacent Uva and central hills. Kumbukkan Oya in the east and Menik River and its tributaries in the west flow across the park, and provide an important water source in the dry season to wild animals of the park. Normally the streams of the park are dry during the [[drought]] season. These rivers and streams exhibit a degree of [[Surface runoff|runoff]] fluctuations between wet and dry seasons. Kumbukkan Oya [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharges]] seven times as much water in the rainy season than in the dry season. A number of lagoons are situated along the coast line of the park.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> There are several routes to get to Yala from [[Colombo]], while the route via [[Ratnapura]] and [[Tissamaharama]] is the shortest with {{convert|270|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n== Impact of the 2004 tsunami ==\nYala lay in the direct path of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]], which impacted Sri Lanka 90 minutes after its generation.<ref name=\"Fernando\">{{cite journal |last=Fernando | first=Prithiviraj |author2=Wikramanayake, Eric D. |author3=Pastorini, Jennifer| date=10 June 2006|title=Impact of tsunami on terrestrial ecosystems of Yala National Park, Sri Lanka|journal=[[Current Science]]|volume=90|issue=11|pages=1531\u20131534|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/jun102006/1531.pdf}}</ref> The tsunami caused severe but localized damage on the park,<ref name=\"Ratnayake\">{{cite journal|last=L. Ratnayake|first=Ranitha|title=Impact of tsunami disaster on the integral Yala National Park (Sri Lanka) vegetation cover using remote sensing|location=Sri Lanka|url=http://www.ceg.ncl.ac.uk/rspsoc2007/papers/77.pdf}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> with around 250 people being killed.<ref name=\"noticias.info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.noticias.info/Archivo/2004/200412/20041228/20041228_43464.shtm|title=Earthquake: Tsunami closes Yala Park|date=28 December 2004|work=noticias.info|accessdate=18 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220163330/http://www.noticias.info/Archivo/2004/200412/20041228/20041228_43464.shtm|archive-date=20 February 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The tsunami wave was reported to be {{convert|20|ft|m}} high. The tsunami waves reached inland only through the river-mouth gaps in the [[dune|coastal dunes]].<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=A. L.|first2=B. G.|first3= N.|date=December 2007|title=2004 South Asia tsunami left little record of its trace near Yala, southeastern Sri Lanka|bibcode=2007AGUFMOS31A0168M|last2=McAdoo|last3=Ranasinghe|volume=31|pages=OS31A\u20130168|journal=American Geophysical Union, Fall Meeting}}</ref> Inundation distances from ranged up to {{convert|392|to|1490|m|yd}}. The main habitats affected are scrub forest and grasslands. About {{convert|5,000|ha|mi2}} of grassland, forest, and wetland were directly affected by the tsunami. The [[Satellite imagery|satellite images]] revealed that mean [[Normalized Difference Vegetation Index]] (NDVI) range from 0.245\u20130.772 in the Block I and II. After the disaster the NDVI value fell dramatically to 0.2111. Around 60% of the area along the coastline has changed. The damage was worse closer to the sea.<ref name=\"Ratnayake\" /> The movement patterns of two [[Tracking collar|radio collared]] elephants were analyzed. The study found out that their movements were consistent with behaviour prompted by immediate cues generated by the tsunami waves rather than a response to a \"sixth sense\".<ref name=\"Wikramanayake\">{{cite journal|last=Wikramanayake|first=Eric|author2=Fernando, Prithiviraj |author3=Leimgruber, Peter |year=2006|title=Behavioral Response of Satellite-collared Elephants to the Tsunami in Southern Sri Lanka|journal=Biotropica|volume=38|issue=6|pages=775\u2013777|url=http://si-pddr.si.edu/dspace/bitstream/10088/6047/1/41A3412A-04F5-48D1-86A7-8BF03813F28B.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1744-7429.2006.00199.x}}</ref>\n\n== Flora ==\n[[File:Yala Wetland.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A water stream and dead trees in a wetland|Wetlands are one of habitat types of Yala]]\n\nYala National Park has a variety of [[ecosystem]]s including [[Sri Lanka lowland rain forests|moist monsoon forests]], [[Sri Lanka dry-zone dry evergreen forests|dry monsoon forests]], [[Deccan thorn scrub forests|semi deciduous forests, thorn forests]], [[grassland]]s, marshes, marine [[wetland]]s, and sandy beaches.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The area under forest cover mainly consists of Block I and [[rangeland]]s of open parkland (''Pelessa'' grasslands) including some extensive grasslands. The forest area is restricted to around the Menik River while rangelands are found towards the sea side. Other habitat types of the Block I are tanks and water holes, lagoons and [[mangrove]]s and [[Shifting cultivation|chena lands]]. The mangrove vegetation in the Buthuwa lagoon is largely ''Rhizophora mucronata'' while ''[[Avicennia]]'' spp. and ''[[Aegiceras]]'' spp. are less abundant. The vegetation of Block II is similar to those of Block I, and Yalawela, once a fertile [[paddy field]], represents ''Pitiya'' grasslands. The mangroves of Block II occur around the estuary of Menik River, which extent to {{convert|100|ha|mi2}}. The common mangrove plants are ''Rhizophora mucronata'', ''Sonneratia caseolaris'', ''Avicennia'' spp., and ''Aegiceras corniculatum''. The lagoons of Pilinnawa, Mahapothana, and Pahalapothana are also located in this block.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The other common mangrove species are ''Sonneratia caseolaris'', ''Acanthus ilicifolius'', ''Excoecaria agallocha'', and ''Lumnitzera racemosa''. In the bare sand ''Crinum zeylanicum'' is found.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite book|last=Green|first=Micahael J. B.|title=IUCN directory of South Asian protected areas|publisher=[[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]]|year=1990|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofs90gree/page/242 242]\u2013246|isbn=978-2-8317-0030-4|url=https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofs90gree}}</ref>\n\nIn the Blocks III, IV, and V, forests are more widespread. The [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]] of the forest mainly contains ''Drypetes sepiaria'' and ''[[Manilkara hexandra]]'' plant species. The ''Pitiya'' grasslands are important for [[grazing]] animals. ''Cynodon barberi'' is the common grass in ''Pitiya'' grasslands while ''[[Zoysia matrella]]'' becomes dominant near the beach. Among 300 odd floral species are ''[[Manilkara hexandra]]'', ''Drypetes sepiaria'', [[Chloroxylon|Ceylon Satinwood]], ''[[Terminalia arjuna]]'', [[Limonia (plant)|limonia]], ''[[Berrya cordifolia]]'', ''Randia dumetorum'', ''Pleurostylia opposita'', ''[[Gymnema sylvestre]]'', [[Dichrostachys cinerea|Bell mimosa]], [[Neem]], [[Ficus benghalensis|Banyan]], [[Salvadora persica|Toothbrush tree]], ''Schleichera oleosa'', ''[[Vitex pinnata]]'', [[Jambul|Indian blackberry]], ''Gmelina asiatica'', ''[[Carissa spinarum]]'', ''Euphorbia antiquorum'', and ''Acacia eburnea''.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> In the seasonally flooded areas of Block II, a wild species of [[Oryza|rice]] is found. ''[[Glenniea unijuga]]'' is an endemic plant species found around the wetlands of the park. ''Munronia pumila'', ''Salacia reticulata'', and ''[[Asparagus racemosus]]'' are some [[Herbalism|medicinal plants]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\n== Fauna ==\n\n=== Birds ===\n[[File:Thimindu 2009 09 27 Yala Great Stone Curlew 2.JPG|thumb|alt= A large black and white bird in a grassy field|The [[great stone-curlew]] (great thick-knee) is a waterbird found in the park]]\n\nYala is one of the 70 [[Important Bird Area]]s (IBAs) in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"birdlife.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sites/index.html?action=SitHTMDetails.asp&sid=15329&m=0|title=Important Bird Area factsheet: Yala, Sri Lanka|year=2009|work=birdlife.org|publisher=[[BirdLife International]]|accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> Of 215 bird species of the park, seven are endemic to Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> They are [[Sri Lanka grey hornbill]], [[Sri Lanka junglefowl]], [[Sri Lanka wood pigeon]], [[crimson-fronted barbet]], [[Black-crested bulbul|black-capped bulbul]], [[blue-tailed bee-eater]] and [[brown-capped babbler]]. The number of waterbirds inhabiting wetlands of Yala is 90 and half of them are [[Bird migration|migrants]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> [[Waterfowl]] ([[lesser whistling duck]], [[garganey]]), cormorants ([[little cormorant]], [[Indian cormorant]]), large waterbirds ([[grey heron]], [[black-headed ibis]], [[Eurasian spoonbill]], [[Asian openbill]], [[painted stork]]), medium-sized waders ''[[Tringa]]'' spp., and small waders ''[[Charadrius]]'' spp. are among the most common waterbirds. [[Black-necked stork]] and [[lesser adjutant]] are many of the rare birds that can be seen in the park. The migrant [[great white pelican]] and resident [[spot-billed pelican]] are also have been recorded. Other waterbirds attracted to the Yala lagoons include [[lesser flamingo]], [[pelican]]s, and rare species such as [[purple heron]], [[Nycticorax|night herons]], [[egret]]s, [[purple swamphen]], and [[Oriental darter]]. Thousands of waterfowls migrate to the lagoons of Yala during the northeast monsoon. They are [[northern pintail]], [[white-winged tern]], [[Eurasian curlew]], [[Eurasian whimbrel]], [[godwit]]s, and [[ruddy turnstone]]. The visiting species mingled with residing [[lesser whistling duck]], [[yellow-wattled lapwing]], [[red-wattled lapwing]], and [[great stone-curlew]]. [[Rock pigeon]], [[barred buttonquail]], [[Indian peafowl]], [[black stork]], [[black-winged stilt]], and [[greater flamingo]] are among the other bird species. [[Crested serpent eagle]] and [[white-bellied sea eagle]] are the [[Bird of prey|raptors]] of the park. The forest birds are [[orange-breasted green pigeon]], [[hornbill]]s, [[Old World flycatcher]]s, [[Indian paradise flycatcher]], [[Megalaimidae|Asian barbets]], and [[Old World oriole|oriole]]s.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Mammals ===\n[[File:Elephant Herd Yala National Park.jpg|thumb|Streams in the park can sustain a large herd of [[Sri Lankan elephant]]s]]\n[[File:Leopards Yala.jpg|thumb|Yala has the highest leopard concentration in the [[Earth|world]]]]\n\nIncluding [[Sri Lankan elephant]], 44 species of mammals are resident in Yala National Park,<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> and it has one of the highest [[leopard]] densities in the world.<ref name=\"Kittle\">{{cite news |url=http://sundaytimes.lk/090510/Plus/sundaytimesplus_12.html |title=Tracking the Lankan Leopard |last=Kittle |first=Andrew |date=May 10, 2009 |work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]] |accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref> 25 individual [[Sri Lankan leopard|leopard]]s are estimated to roam in Block I.<ref name=\"Santiapillai 82\">{{cite journal |last=Santiapillai |first=Charles |author2=Chambers, M.R. |author3=Ishwaran, N.|date=May 1982 |title=The leopard Panthera pardus fusca (meyer 1794) in the ruhuna national park, Sri Lanka, conservation |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=5\u201314 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(82)90050-7}}</ref> The elephant herd of Yala contains 300\u2013350 individuals.<ref name=\"Perera\">{{cite journal |last=Perera |first=B. M. A. Oswin |year=2007 |title=Status of Elephants in Sri Lanka and the Human-Elephant Conflict |url=http://www.vet.cmu.ac.th/elephant/file/9%2014-22%20Oswin.pdf }}{{dead link |date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> The [[Sri Lankan sloth bear]], leopard, elephant, and [[wild water buffalo]] are all threatened mammals that Yala harbours. Although water buffaloes are indigenous to Sri Lanka, most populations contain genes of the [[Cattle|domestic stock]] or have descended from [[feral]] populations. [[Toque macaque]], [[golden palm civet]], [[red slender loris]], and [[fishing cat]] are among the other mammals that can be seen in Yala. The elephant population of the park varies seasonally.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Reptiles ===\n[[File:Crocodile in Yala National Park 2.JPG|thumb|[[Crocodile]]]]\n\nThe reptile fauna recorded from the park is 47 and six of them are endemic. [[Sri Lankan krait]], [[Boulenger's keelback]], [[Sri Lankan flying snake]], [[painted-lip lizard]], [[Wiegmann's agama]], and [[Bahir's fan-throated lizard]] are the endemic species.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /><ref>http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species?genus=Sitana&species=bahiri&search_param=((taxon%3D'agamidae'))\n</ref> The coastal line of the park is visited by the all five globally [[endangered sea turtles]] ([[leatherback turtle]], [[olive ridley]], [[loggerhead sea turtle]], [[hawksbill turtle]], and [[green turtle]]) that visit Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /><ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The two breeding crocodile species of Sri Lanka, [[mugger crocodile]] and [[saltwater crocodile]], inhabit the park. The [[Indian cobra]] and [[Daboia|Russell's viper]] are among the other reptiles.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Amphibians ===\nThere are 18 [[amphibian]] species that have been recorded from Yala, while ''[[Bufo atukoralei]]'' and ''[[Adenomus kelaartii]]'' are endemic to Sri Lanka.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n=== Fish ===\nIn the water courses of Yala, 21 [[freshwater fish]] are found.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> The fish population in the perennial reservoirs contain mostly [[Fish#Exotic species|exotic]] [[fish food|food fish]] [[Oreochromis mossambicus|Mozambique tilapia]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The [[stone sucker]] and ''Esomus thermoicos'' are endemic among other species. The [[Puntius filamentosus|blackspot barb]], [[Puntius sarana|olive barb]], [[orange chromide]] and [[common spiny loach]] are the common fish species.\n\n=== Invertebrates ===\n[[Crab]]s and [[prawn]]s include the fauna in the lagoons of the park.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\nA variety of butterfly species is found here. The [[Graphium sarpedon|common bluebottle]], [[Papilio demoleus|common lime butterfly]], [[Atrophaneura hector|crimson rose]], [[Delias eucharis|common Jezebel]], and [[common Mormon]] are the common species.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n== Cultural importance ==\n[[File:Wild Elephant yala small version.jpg|thumb|Wild elephants are commonly found in Yala. Elephant Rock is in the background]]\n\nYala had been a center of past civilisations.<ref name=\"Green\" /> King [[Ravana]], the mythical Hindu anti-hero is believed to have established [[Lanka|his kingdom]] here with [[Great Basses Reef Lighthouse|Ravana Kotte]], now submerged in the sea, as its boundary.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} Seafaring traders brought Indo-Aryan civilisation with them, as Yala is situated in their trading route. A large number of ancient although disrepaired [[Irrigation tank|tanks]] are the evidence of a rich hydraulic and agricultural civilisation dating back to 5th century BC.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> Situlpahuwa, which was the home for 12,000 [[Arahant (Buddhism)|arahant]]s, is situated within the park area along with Magul Vihara, which built in 87 BC and Akasa Chaitiya, which constructed in 2nd century BC. Agriculture flourished in area during the period of [[Kingdom of Ruhuna|Ruhuna Kingdom]]. According to ''[[Mahavamsa]]'', the Kingdom of Ruhuna began to decline by the end of the 13th Century AD. During the colonial period Yala became a popular hunting ground. Yala is annually visited by 400,000 pilgrims.<ref name=\"Buultjens\">{{cite journal|last=Buultjens|first=J.|author2=Ratnayake, I.|author3=Gnanapala, A.|author4=Aslam, M|year=2005|title=Tourism and its implications for management in Ruhuna National Park (Yala), Sri Lanka|journal=Tourism Management|volume=26|issue=5|pages=733\u2013742|url=http://www.sab.ac.lk/Faculty/Management/tourism/Research/sdarticle.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2004.03.014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061102091806/http://www.sab.ac.lk/Faculty/Management/tourism/Research/sdarticle.pdf|archivedate=2006-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\n[[Poaching]], gem-mining, [[logging]], encroachment by agriculture, and free-roaming domestic [[livestock]] are the main threats to the park.<ref name=\"Green\" /> Three wardens have been killed in clashes with poachers. Gems are mined along the Menik River and holes created by gem mining, which extend up to {{convert|30|m|ft}}, can be seen along the Kumbukkan Oya. In Blocks III and IV, the encroachment is severe as [[shifting cultivation|chena cultivation]] and burning, to provide [[grazing]] in the dry season, collides with the boundary. A large grove of ''Sonneratia caseolaris'' is faced with [[forest dieback]] in the Menik River's estuary. Cultivation of tobacco, [[noise pollution|noise]] and [[air pollution|air]] pollutions caused by uncontrolled tourism are the other [[Environmental issue|conservation issues]]. The growth of [[invasive species|invasive]] [[introduced species|alien]] species such as ''[[Lantana camara]]'', ''[[Opuntia stricta|Opuntia dillenii]]'', ''[[Chromolaena odorata]]'' is threatening the native plants.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\nDeep within the forest, [[Cannabis (drug)|Ganja]] is cultivated in cleared areas.<ref name=\"Green\" /> The wildlife is poached and disturbed by the fishermen at Patanangala. The turtles are caught in fishing nets and the fishermen also litter the beach with debris. They have also set traps inland and dig up turtle nests. In the absence of hand-weeding, which was practiced until the 1950s, the transformation of interior grasslands to [[Shrubland|scrub jungle]] is unavoidable. The tourism has created problems in the past, such as vehicles harassing wild animals. The issue is most severe in Sithulpahuwa where thousands of pilgrims visit, leading to a great degree of commercialisation. [[Department of Wildlife Conservation (Sri Lanka)|Department of Wildlife Conservation]] has taken some conservation measures such as management of grazing lands, conservation of small water ponds, and eradication of invasive alien species. A {{convert|40|km|mi}} long [[electric fence]] was erected to prevent elephants from moving into nearby villages.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Tourism Yala National Park.jpg|thumb|Tourism generates noise and air pollution in the park, but also generates money and therefore helps to justify the National Park]]\n\nThe Yala National Park is the most visited park in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> In 2002 around 156,867 tourists visited the park. Foreigners, especially Europeans, account for 30% of total visitors.<ref name=\"Weerasinghe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/DOCREP/ARTICLE/WFC/XII/0116-A1.HTM|title=Ruhuna (Yala) National Park in Sri Lanka: visitors, visitation and Eco-tourism|last=Weerasinghe|first=U. M. I. R. K. |author2=Kariyawasm, Dayananda |author3=De Zoysa, Mangala|work=fao.org|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref> Block I is the main area for visits. Block III (main gate in Galge area, on Buttala-Kataragama Road) and the adjoining '''Kumana Park''' or 'Yala East'  (main gate at Okanda, on the east coast not far from Pottuvil) however are becoming popular in their own right too.\n\nNote that the Situlpahuwa pilgrimage site, geographically in Block III, has kind of an 'enclave' status and is accessible FOC through separate roads from Tissa and Kataragama. Most of the visitors stated that reasons for their visit is to see wild animals, and elephant is the most preferred animal. The visitors like to see bears, leopards, birds as well. In 2000 the income from visitors including lodge fees was approximately {{USD}}468,629.<ref name=\"Buultjens\" /> Due to security conditions revenue was lost.<ref name=\"Sunday Observer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/07/26/imp10.asp|title=Revamping national parks in a post-war setting|last=Prematunge|first=Sajitha|date=26 July 2009|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=17 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605233821/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/07/26/imp10.asp|archivedate=5 June 2011}}</ref> The Yala National Park has been susceptible to terrorist attacks. On 17 October 2007 a group of [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|LTTE]] cadres attacked an army detachment in Thalgasmankada in the park.<ref name=\"Sunday Observer 2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/21/fea02.asp|title=Not a feather in Tiger cap|date=21 October 2007|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123124048/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/21/fea02.asp|archivedate=23 January 2008}}</ref> The attack killed six [[Sri Lanka Army|army soldiers]] and another was caught up in a landmine explosion. On 11 July 2008 four people died in an attack launched by the LTTE.<ref name=\"Daily News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/07/12/sec01.asp|title=Tigers fire at bus killing four|last=Wijayapala|first=Ranil|author2=Yatawara, Daneshi|date=12 July 2008|work=Daily News|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604213030/http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/07/12/sec01.asp|archivedate=4 June 2011}}</ref> The cadres opened fire at a bus carrying pilgrims to [[Kataragama]]. Since the end of the civil war, May 2009, no violence has occurred in Yala area also and it is fully safe for visitors; this was also the main factor in opening blocks III and V for tourists.\n\nFrom January to June in 2008, 9,078 local tourists and 7,532 foreigners have visited Yala. For the same period of time in 2009 the arrivals have risen to 18,031 locals and foreigners to 10,439. Accordingly, the revenue increased to Rs. 27 million ({{USD}}235,000) in 2009 from Rs. 16.6 million ({{USD}}154,000) in 2008. The visitors are allowed to see the wild animals from 5.30 am to 6.30 pm.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> Due to [[drought]]s the park used to be closed to tourists from 1 September, to 15 October annually; however in 2009 and 2010 the closure was skipped and lakes filled with water bowsers for drinking water for the animals, a future strategy on drought handling is not yet clear.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.yalasrilanka.lk Official website for Yala National Park]\n* [https://www.attractionsinsrilanka.com/travel-directory/yala-national-park/ Yala National Park bungalows]\n*[https://www.imperialyalasafari.com/ yala safari jeep tour]\n\n{{commonscat-inline|Yala National Park}}\n{{National Parks of Sri Lanka}}\n\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:National parks of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1900]]\n[[Category:Protected areas in Southern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Protected areas in Uva Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Yala National Park\n| alt_name = {{lang|si|\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd \u0da2\u0dcf\u0dad\u0dd2\u0d9a \u0dc0\u0db1\u0ddd\u0daf\u0dca\u200d\u0dba\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dba}}<br/>{{lang|ta|\u0baf\u0bbe\u0bb2 \u0ba4\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf \u0bb5\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd}}\n| iucn_category = II\n| map = Sri Lanka\n| relief = yes\n| map_width = 220\n| map_caption = Location of Yala National Park\n| photo = Yala Beach.jpg\n| photo_caption = Patanangala, a rock outcrop in the Yala beach\n| photo_alt = Sandy beach with a rocky outcrop in sea side\n| location = [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern]] and [[Uva Province|Uva]] Provinces, [[Sri Lanka]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hambantota]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|6|22|22|N|81|31|01|E|display=inline, title}}\n| area_km2 = 978.807\n| established = 1900 (Wildlife sanctuary)<br/> 1938 (National park)\n| visitation_num =\n| visitation_year =\n| governing_body = [[Department of Wildlife Conservation (Sri Lanka)|Department of Wildlife Conservation]]\n| website ={{url|www.yalasrilanka.lk}}\n}}\n\n'''Yala (\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dbd) National Park''' is the most visited and second largest [[national park]] in [[Sri Lanka]], bordering the [[Indian Ocean]]. The park consists of five blocks, two of which are now open to the public, and also adjoining parks. The blocks have individual names such as, '''Ruhuna National Park''' (Block 1), and [[Kumana National Park]] or 'Yala East' for the adjoining area. It is situated in the southeast region of the country, and lies in [[Southern Province, Sri Lanka|Southern Province]] and [[Uva Province]]. The park covers {{convert|979|km2|mi2}} and is located about {{convert|300|km|mi}} from [[Colombo]]. Yala was designated as a [[Wildlife refuge|wildlife sanctuary]] in 1900, and, along with [[Wilpattu National Park|Wilpattu]] was one of the first two national parks in Sri Lanka, having been designated in 1938. The park is best known for its variety of wild animals. It is important for the conservation of [[Sri Lankan elephant]]s, [[Sri Lankan leopard]]s and aquatic birds.\n\nThere are six national parks and three wildlife sanctuaries in the vicinity of Yala. Among the largest is [[Lunugamvehera National Park]]. The park is situated in the [[Geography of Sri Lanka#Climate|dry semi-arid climatic region]] and rain is received mainly during the [[monsoon|northeast monsoon]]. Yala hosts a variety of [[ecosystem]]s ranging from moist monsoon forests to freshwater and marine [[wetland]]s. It is one of the 70 [[Important Bird Area]]s (IBAs) in Sri Lanka. Yala harbours 215 bird species including six endemic species of Sri Lanka. The number of [[mammal]]s that has been recorded from the park is 44, and it has one of the highest [[leopard]] densities in the world.\n\nThe area around Yala has hosted several ancient civilizations. Two important pilgrim sites, '''Sithulpahuwa''' and '''Magul Vihara''', are situated within the park. The [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]] caused severe damage on the Yala National Park and 250 people died in its vicinity. The number of visitors has been on the rise since 2009, after the security situation in the park improved.\n\n== History ==\nIn 1560 Spanish cartographer Cipriano Sanchez noted Yala in his map \"is abandoned for 300 years due to insalubrious conditions.\"<ref name=\"Brohier\" >{{cite book |last=Brohier |first=R. L. |title=Brohier dutu Lankawa |trans-title=The Ceylon that Brohier seen |editor=Hewawasam, Abhaya |publisher=Sooriya Publishers |year=2001 |edition=2nd |isbn=978-955-9348-63-4 |pages=312\u2013320 |language=Sinhala}}</ref> Chief Justice Sir [[Alexander Johnston (1775\u20131849)|Alexander Johnston]] wrote a detailed account on Yala in 1806 after travelling from [[Trincomalee]] to [[Hambantota]]. On March 23, 1900 the government proclaimed Yala and [[Wilpattu National Park|Wilpattu]] reserves under the Forest Ordinance.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\">{{cite book |last=Senaratna |first=P.M. |title=Sri Lankawe Jathika Vanodhyana |publisher=Sarasavi Publishers |year=2009 |edition=2nd |pages=22\u201369 |chapter=Yala |isbn=978-955-573-346-5 |language=Sinhala}}</ref> Initially the extent of the reserve was {{convert|389|km2|mi2}} between the Menik  and Kumbukkan Rivers. At that time the reserve did not bear the name Yala. The Game Protection Society (now the Wildlife and Nature Protection Society) was instrumental in establishing the reserve. The forest area between Palatupana and Yala was declared a hunting site reserved only for the resident sportsmen.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> [[Henry Engelbrecht]] was appointed as the first park warden.\n\n[[File:Yala Map.jpg|thumb|350px|Map of the National Park]]\nOn 1 March 1938, Yala became a national park when the Flora and Fauna Protection Ordinance was passed into law by [[Don Stephen Senanayake|D. S. Senanayake]], the minister of agriculture. The park consists of five blocks.<ref name=\"iwmi\">{{cite web|url=http://dw.iwmi.org/wetland_profile/Ruhuna.asp|title=Ruhuna National Park|work=Sri Lanka Wetlands Information and Database|publisher=[[International Water Management Institute]]|accessdate=15 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726201837/http://dw.iwmi.org/wetland_profile/Ruhuna.asp|archivedate=26 July 2011}}</ref> Subsequently, four other blocks were incorporated to the park. There are six national parks and three wildlife sanctuaries in the vicinity of Yala. [[Kumana National Park]], Yala Strict Nature Reserve and Kataragama, Katagamuwa, and Nimalawa sanctuaries are continuous with the park.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Block\n! Extent\n! Date added to the park\n|-\n| Block I\n| {{convert|14,101|ha|mi2}}\n| 1938\n|-\n| Block II\n| {{convert|9,931|ha|mi2}}\n| 1954\n|-\n| Block III\n| {{convert|40,775|ha|mi2}}\n| 1967\n|-\n| Block IV\n| {{convert|26,418|ha|mi2}}\n| 1969\n|-\n| Block V\n| {{convert|6,656|ha|mi2}}\n| 1973\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" | Source: ''Sri Lanka Wetlands Information and Database''<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n|}\n\n== Physical features ==\n[[File:Yalapond.jpg|thumb|alt=A dead tree by a body of water|Surface water becomes critical in the dry season]]\n\nThe Yala area is mostly composed of [[metamorphic rock]] belonging to the [[Precambrian]] era and classified into two series, Vijayan series and Highland series. Reddish brown soil and low [[Humus|humic]] grey soil are prominent among six [[soil type]]s. Yala is situated in the lowest [[peneplain]] of Sri Lanka, which extends from Trincomalee to Hambantota.  Topographically the area is a flat and mildly undulating plain that runs to the coast with elevation is {{convert|30|m|ft}} close to the coast while rising in the interior to {{convert|100|-|125|m|ft}}. The national park is situated in the [[Geography of Sri Lanka#Climate|dry semi-arid climatic region]] and rain is received mainly during the [[monsoon|northeast monsoon]]. The mean annual rainfall ranges between {{convert|500|-|775|mm|in}} while the mean temperature ranges between {{convert|26.4|C|F}} in January to {{convert|30|C|F}} in April. It is  windier in Yala, during the southwest monsoon compared to the wind during the northeast monsoon with wind speeds from {{convert|23|km/h|mi/h}} to {{convert|15|km/h|mi/h}}.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\nWater is abundant after the northeast monsoon, but during the dry season surface water becomes an important factor. The bodies of surface water appear in the forms of [[stream]]s, tanks, waterholes, rock pools, and [[lagoon]]s. Waterholes occur in low lying places while rock pools of varying size are capable of containing water year-round, and are hence an important source of water for elephants. For many water birds and [[Water Buffalo|water buffaloes]] natural waterholes are ideal habitats. Such reservoirs are largely concentrated to the Block I followed by Block II. Several tanks  are there including, Maha Seelawa, Buthawa, Uraniya, and Pilinnawa tanks.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> Many rivers and streams flow in a southeasterly direction, originating in the highlands of adjacent Uva and central hills. Kumbukkan Oya in the east and Menik River and its tributaries in the west flow across the park, and provide an important water source in the dry season to wild animals of the park. Normally the streams of the park are dry during the [[drought]] season. These rivers and streams exhibit a degree of [[Surface runoff|runoff]] fluctuations between wet and dry seasons. Kumbukkan Oya [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharges]] seven times as much water in the rainy season than in the dry season. A number of lagoons are situated along the coast line of the park.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> There are several routes to get to Yala from [[Colombo]], while the route via [[Ratnapura]] and [[Tissamaharama]] is the shortest with {{convert|270|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n== Impact of the 2004 tsunami ==\nYala lay in the direct path of the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake|2004 Indian Ocean tsunami]], which impacted Sri Lanka 90 minutes after its generation.<ref name=\"Fernando\">{{cite journal |last=Fernando | first=Prithiviraj |author2=Wikramanayake, Eric D. |author3=Pastorini, Jennifer| date=10 June 2006|title=Impact of tsunami on terrestrial ecosystems of Yala National Park, Sri Lanka|journal=[[Current Science]]|volume=90|issue=11|pages=1531\u20131534|url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/jun102006/1531.pdf}}</ref> The tsunami caused severe but localized damage on the park,<ref name=\"Ratnayake\">{{cite journal|last=L. Ratnayake|first=Ranitha|title=Impact of tsunami disaster on the integral Yala National Park (Sri Lanka) vegetation cover using remote sensing|location=Sri Lanka|url=http://www.ceg.ncl.ac.uk/rspsoc2007/papers/77.pdf}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> with around 250 people being killed.<ref name=\"noticias.info\">{{cite web|url=http://www.noticias.info/Archivo/2004/200412/20041228/20041228_43464.shtm|title=Earthquake: Tsunami closes Yala Park|date=28 December 2004|work=noticias.info|accessdate=18 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220163330/http://www.noticias.info/Archivo/2004/200412/20041228/20041228_43464.shtm|archive-date=20 February 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The tsunami wave was reported to be {{convert|20|ft|m}} high. The tsunami waves reached inland only through the river-mouth gaps in the [[dune|coastal dunes]].<ref name=\"Moore\">{{cite journal|last=Moore|first=A. L.|first2=B. G.|first3= N.|date=December 2007|title=2004 South Asia tsunami left little record of its trace near Yala, southeastern Sri Lanka|bibcode=2007AGUFMOS31A0168M|last2=McAdoo|last3=Ranasinghe|volume=31|pages=OS31A\u20130168|journal=American Geophysical Union, Fall Meeting}}</ref> Inundation distances from ranged up to {{convert|392|to|1490|m|yd}}. The main habitats affected are scrub forest and grasslands. About {{convert|5,000|ha|mi2}} of grassland, forest, and wetland were directly affected by the tsunami. The [[Satellite imagery|satellite images]] revealed that mean [[Normalized Difference Vegetation Index]] (NDVI) range from 0.245\u20130.772 in the Block I and II. After the disaster the NDVI value fell dramatically to 0.2111. Around 60% of the area along the coastline has changed. The damage was worse closer to the sea.<ref name=\"Ratnayake\" /> The movement patterns of two [[Tracking collar|radio collared]] elephants were analyzed. The study found out that their movements were consistent with behaviour prompted by immediate cues generated by the tsunami waves rather than a response to a \"sixth sense\".<ref name=\"Wikramanayake\">{{cite journal|last=Wikramanayake|first=Eric|author2=Fernando, Prithiviraj |author3=Leimgruber, Peter |year=2006|title=Behavioral Response of Satellite-collared Elephants to the Tsunami in Southern Sri Lanka|journal=Biotropica|volume=38|issue=6|pages=775\u2013777|url=http://si-pddr.si.edu/dspace/bitstream/10088/6047/1/41A3412A-04F5-48D1-86A7-8BF03813F28B.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1744-7429.2006.00199.x}}</ref>\n\n== Flora ==\n[[File:Yala Wetland.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A water stream and dead trees in a wetland|Wetlands are one of habitat types of Yala]]\n\nYala National Park has a variety of [[ecosystem]]s including [[Sri Lanka lowland rain forests|moist monsoon forests]], [[Sri Lanka dry-zone dry evergreen forests|dry monsoon forests]], [[Deccan thorn scrub forests|semi deciduous forests, thorn forests]], [[grassland]]s, marshes, marine [[wetland]]s, and sandy beaches.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The area under forest cover mainly consists of Block I and [[rangeland]]s of open parkland (''Pelessa'' grasslands) including some extensive grasslands. The forest area is restricted to around the Menik River while rangelands are found towards the sea side. Other habitat types of the Block I are tanks and water holes, lagoons and [[mangrove]]s and [[Shifting cultivation|chena lands]]. The mangrove vegetation in the Buthuwa lagoon is largely ''Rhizophora mucronata'' while ''[[Avicennia]]'' spp. and ''[[Aegiceras]]'' spp. are less abundant. The vegetation of Block II is similar to those of Block I, and Yalawela, once a fertile [[paddy field]], represents ''Pitiya'' grasslands. The mangroves of Block II occur around the estuary of Menik River, which extent to {{convert|100|ha|mi2}}. The common mangrove plants are ''Rhizophora mucronata'', ''Sonneratia caseolaris'', ''Avicennia'' spp., and ''Aegiceras corniculatum''. The lagoons of Pilinnawa, Mahapothana, and Pahalapothana are also located in this block.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The other common mangrove species are ''Sonneratia caseolaris'', ''Acanthus ilicifolius'', ''Excoecaria agallocha'', and ''Lumnitzera racemosa''. In the bare sand ''Crinum zeylanicum'' is found.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite book|last=Green|first=Micahael J. B.|title=IUCN directory of South Asian protected areas|publisher=[[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]]|year=1990|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofs90gree/page/242 242]\u2013246|isbn=978-2-8317-0030-4|url=https://archive.org/details/iucndirectoryofs90gree}}</ref>\n\nIn the Blocks III, IV, and V, forests are more widespread. The [[Canopy (biology)|canopy]] of the forest mainly contains ''Drypetes sepiaria'' and ''[[Manilkara hexandra]]'' plant species. The ''Pitiya'' grasslands are important for [[grazing]] animals. ''Cynodon barberi'' is the common grass in ''Pitiya'' grasslands while ''[[Zoysia matrella]]'' becomes dominant near the beach. Among 300 odd floral species are ''[[Manilkara hexandra]]'', ''Drypetes sepiaria'', [[Chloroxylon|Ceylon Satinwood]], ''[[Terminalia arjuna]]'', [[Limonia (plant)|limonia]], ''[[Berrya cordifolia]]'', ''Randia dumetorum'', ''Pleurostylia opposita'', ''[[Gymnema sylvestre]]'', [[Dichrostachys cinerea|Bell mimosa]], [[Neem]], [[Ficus benghalensis|Banyan]], [[Salvadora persica|Toothbrush tree]], ''Schleichera oleosa'', ''[[Vitex pinnata]]'', [[Jambul|Indian blackberry]], ''Gmelina asiatica'', ''[[Carissa spinarum]]'', ''Euphorbia antiquorum'', and ''Acacia eburnea''.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> In the seasonally flooded areas of Block II, a wild species of [[Oryza|rice]] is found. ''[[Glenniea unijuga]]'' is an endemic plant species found around the wetlands of the park. ''Munronia pumila'', ''Salacia reticulata'', and ''[[Asparagus racemosus]]'' are some [[Herbalism|medicinal plants]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\n== Fauna ==\n\n=== Birds ===\n[[File:Thimindu 2009 09 27 Yala Great Stone Curlew 2.JPG|thumb|alt= A large black and white bird in a grassy field|The [[great stone-curlew]] (great thick-knee) is a waterbird found in the park]]\n\nYala is one of the 70 [[Important Bird Area]]s (IBAs) in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"birdlife.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sites/index.html?action=SitHTMDetails.asp&sid=15329&m=0|title=Important Bird Area factsheet: Yala, Sri Lanka|year=2009|work=birdlife.org|publisher=[[BirdLife International]]|accessdate=18 March 2010}}</ref> Of 215 bird species of the park, seven are endemic to Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> They are [[Sri Lanka grey hornbill]], [[Sri Lanka junglefowl]], [[Sri Lanka wood pigeon]], [[crimson-fronted barbet]], [[Black-crested bulbul|black-capped bulbul]], [[blue-tailed bee-eater]] and [[brown-capped babbler]]. The number of waterbirds inhabiting wetlands of Yala is 90 and half of them are [[Bird migration|migrants]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> [[Waterfowl]] ([[lesser whistling duck]], [[garganey]]), cormorants ([[little cormorant]], [[Indian cormorant]]), large waterbirds ([[grey heron]], [[black-headed ibis]], [[Eurasian spoonbill]], [[Asian openbill]], [[painted stork]]), medium-sized waders ''[[Tringa]]'' spp., and small waders ''[[Charadrius]]'' spp. are among the most common waterbirds. [[Black-necked stork]] and [[lesser adjutant]] are many of the rare birds that can be seen in the park. The migrant [[great white pelican]] and resident [[spot-billed pelican]] are also have been recorded. Other waterbirds attracted to the Yala lagoons include [[lesser flamingo]], [[pelican]]s, and rare species such as [[purple heron]], [[Nycticorax|night herons]], [[egret]]s, [[purple swamphen]], and [[Oriental darter]]. Thousands of waterfowls migrate to the lagoons of Yala during the northeast monsoon. They are [[northern pintail]], [[white-winged tern]], [[Eurasian curlew]], [[Eurasian whimbrel]], [[godwit]]s, and [[ruddy turnstone]]. The visiting species mingled with residing [[lesser whistling duck]], [[yellow-wattled lapwing]], [[red-wattled lapwing]], and [[great stone-curlew]]. [[Rock pigeon]], [[barred buttonquail]], [[Indian peafowl]], [[black stork]], [[black-winged stilt]], and [[greater flamingo]] are among the other bird species. [[Crested serpent eagle]] and [[white-bellied sea eagle]] are the [[Bird of prey|raptors]] of the park. The forest birds are [[orange-breasted green pigeon]], [[hornbill]]s, [[Old World flycatcher]]s, [[Indian paradise flycatcher]], [[Megalaimidae|Asian barbets]], and [[Old World oriole|oriole]]s.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Mammals ===\n[[File:Elephant Herd Yala National Park.jpg|thumb|Streams in the park can sustain a large herd of [[Sri Lankan elephant]]s]]\n[[File:Leopards Yala.jpg|thumb|Yala has the highest leopard concentration in the [[Earth|world]]]]\n\nIncluding [[Sri Lankan elephant]], 44 species of mammals are resident in Yala National Park,<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> and it has one of the highest [[leopard]] densities in the world.<ref name=\"Kittle\">{{cite news |url=http://sundaytimes.lk/090510/Plus/sundaytimesplus_12.html |title=Tracking the Lankan Leopard |last=Kittle |first=Andrew |date=May 10, 2009 |work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]] |accessdate=27 February 2010}}</ref> 25 individual [[Sri Lankan leopard|leopard]]s are estimated to roam in Block I.<ref name=\"Santiapillai 82\">{{cite journal |last=Santiapillai |first=Charles |author2=Chambers, M.R. |author3=Ishwaran, N.|date=May 1982 |title=The leopard Panthera pardus fusca (meyer 1794) in the ruhuna national park, Sri Lanka, conservation |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=5\u201314 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(82)90050-7}}</ref> The elephant herd of Yala contains 300\u2013350 individuals.<ref name=\"Perera\">{{cite journal |last=Perera |first=B. M. A. Oswin |year=2007 |title=Status of Elephants in Sri Lanka and the Human-Elephant Conflict |url=http://www.vet.cmu.ac.th/elephant/file/9%2014-22%20Oswin.pdf }}{{dead link |date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> The [[Sri Lankan sloth bear]], leopard, elephant, and [[wild water buffalo]] are all threatened mammals that Yala harbours. Although water buffaloes are indigenous to Sri Lanka, most populations contain genes of the [[Cattle|domestic stock]] or have descended from [[feral]] populations. [[Toque macaque]], [[golden palm civet]], [[red slender loris]], and [[fishing cat]] are among the other mammals that can be seen in Yala. The elephant population of the park varies seasonally.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Reptiles ===\n[[File:Crocodile in Yala National Park 2.JPG|thumb|[[Crocodile]]]]\n\nThe reptile fauna recorded from the park is 47 and six of them are endemic. [[Sri Lankan krait]], [[Boulenger's keelback]], [[Sri Lankan flying snake]], [[painted-lip lizard]], [[Wiegmann's agama]], and [[Bahir's fan-throated lizard]] are the endemic species.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /><ref>http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species?genus=Sitana&species=bahiri&search_param=((taxon%3D'agamidae'))\n</ref> The coastal line of the park is visited by the all five globally [[endangered sea turtles]] ([[leatherback turtle]], [[olive ridley]], [[loggerhead sea turtle]], [[hawksbill turtle]], and [[green turtle]]) that visit Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /><ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The two breeding crocodile species of Sri Lanka, [[mugger crocodile]] and [[saltwater crocodile]], inhabit the park. The [[Indian cobra]] and [[Daboia|Russell's viper]] are among the other reptiles.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\n=== Amphibians ===\nThere are 18 [[amphibian]] species that have been recorded from Yala, while ''[[Bufo atukoralei]]'' and ''[[Adenomus kelaartii]]'' are endemic to Sri Lanka.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n=== Fish ===\nIn the water courses of Yala, 21 [[freshwater fish]] are found.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> The fish population in the perennial reservoirs contain mostly [[Fish#Exotic species|exotic]] [[fish food|food fish]] [[Oreochromis mossambicus|Mozambique tilapia]].<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> The [[stone sucker]] and ''Esomus thermoicos'' are endemic among other species. The [[Puntius filamentosus|blackspot barb]], [[Puntius sarana|olive barb]], [[orange chromide]] and [[common spiny loach]] are the common fish species.\n\n=== Invertebrates ===\n[[Crab]]s and [[prawn]]s include the fauna in the lagoons of the park.<ref name=\"Green\" />\n\nA variety of butterfly species is found here. The [[Graphium sarpedon|common bluebottle]], [[Papilio demoleus|common lime butterfly]], [[Atrophaneura hector|crimson rose]], [[Delias eucharis|common Jezebel]], and [[common Mormon]] are the common species.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" />\n\n== Cultural importance ==\n[[File:Wild Elephant yala small version.jpg|thumb|Wild elephants are commonly found in Yala. Elephant Rock is in the background]]\n\nYala had been a center of past civilisations.<ref name=\"Green\" /> King [[Ravana]], the mythical Hindu anti-hero is believed to have established [[Lanka|his kingdom]] here with [[Great Basses Reef Lighthouse|Ravana Kotte]], now submerged in the sea, as its boundary.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} Seafaring traders brought Indo-Aryan civilisation with them, as Yala is situated in their trading route. A large number of ancient although disrepaired [[Irrigation tank|tanks]] are the evidence of a rich hydraulic and agricultural civilisation dating back to 5th century BC.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> Situlpahuwa, which was the home for 12,000 [[Arahant (Buddhism)|arahant]]s, is situated within the park area along with Magul Vihara, which built in 87 BC and Akasa Chaitiya, which constructed in 2nd century BC. Agriculture flourished in area during the period of [[Kingdom of Ruhuna|Ruhuna Kingdom]]. According to ''[[Mahavamsa]]'', the Kingdom of Ruhuna began to decline by the end of the 13th Century AD. During the colonial period Yala became a popular hunting ground. Yala is annually visited by 400,000 pilgrims.<ref name=\"Buultjens\">{{cite journal|last=Buultjens|first=J.|author2=Ratnayake, I.|author3=Gnanapala, A.|author4=Aslam, M|year=2005|title=Tourism and its implications for management in Ruhuna National Park (Yala), Sri Lanka|journal=Tourism Management|volume=26|issue=5|pages=733\u2013742|url=http://www.sab.ac.lk/Faculty/Management/tourism/Research/sdarticle.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2004.03.014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061102091806/http://www.sab.ac.lk/Faculty/Management/tourism/Research/sdarticle.pdf|archivedate=2006-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\n[[Poaching]], gem-mining, [[logging]], encroachment by agriculture, and free-roaming domestic [[livestock]] are the main threats to the park.<ref name=\"Green\" /> Three wardens have been killed in clashes with poachers. Gems are mined along the Menik River and holes created by gem mining, which extend up to {{convert|30|m|ft}}, can be seen along the Kumbukkan Oya. In Blocks III and IV, the encroachment is severe as [[shifting cultivation|chena cultivation]] and burning, to provide [[grazing]] in the dry season, collides with the boundary. A large grove of ''Sonneratia caseolaris'' is faced with [[forest dieback]] in the Menik River's estuary. Cultivation of tobacco, [[noise pollution|noise]] and [[air pollution|air]] pollutions caused by uncontrolled tourism are the other [[Environmental issue|conservation issues]]. The growth of [[invasive species|invasive]] [[introduced species|alien]] species such as ''[[Lantana camara]]'', ''[[Opuntia stricta|Opuntia dillenii]]'', ''[[Chromolaena odorata]]'' is threatening the native plants.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\nDeep within the forest, [[Cannabis (drug)|Ganja]] is cultivated in cleared areas.<ref name=\"Green\" /> The wildlife is poached and disturbed by the fishermen at Patanangala. The turtles are caught in fishing nets and the fishermen also litter the beach with debris. They have also set traps inland and dig up turtle nests. In the absence of hand-weeding, which was practiced until the 1950s, the transformation of interior grasslands to [[Shrubland|scrub jungle]] is unavoidable. The tourism has created problems in the past, such as vehicles harassing wild animals. The issue is most severe in Sithulpahuwa where thousands of pilgrims visit, leading to a great degree of commercialisation. [[Department of Wildlife Conservation (Sri Lanka)|Department of Wildlife Conservation]] has taken some conservation measures such as management of grazing lands, conservation of small water ponds, and eradication of invasive alien species. A {{convert|40|km|mi}} long [[electric fence]] was erected to prevent elephants from moving into nearby villages.<ref name=\"iwmi\" />\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Tourism Yala National Park.jpg|thumb|Tourism generates noise and air pollution in the park, but also generates money and therefore helps to justify the National Park]]\n\nThe Yala National Park is the most visited park in Sri Lanka.<ref name=\"iwmi\" /> In 2002 around 156,867 tourists visited the park. Foreigners, especially Europeans, account for 30% of total visitors.<ref name=\"Weerasinghe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/DOCREP/ARTICLE/WFC/XII/0116-A1.HTM|title=Ruhuna (Yala) National Park in Sri Lanka: visitors, visitation and Eco-tourism|last=Weerasinghe|first=U. M. I. R. K. |author2=Kariyawasm, Dayananda |author3=De Zoysa, Mangala|work=fao.org|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref> Block I is the main area for visits. Block III (main gate in Galge area, on Buttala-Kataragama Road) and the adjoining '''Kumana Park''' or 'Yala East'  (main gate at Okanda, on the east coast not far from Pottuvil) however are becoming popular in their own right too.\n\nNote that the Situlpahuwa pilgrimage site, geographically in Block III, has kind of an 'enclave' status and is accessible FOC through separate roads from Tissa and Kataragama. Most of the visitors stated that reasons for their visit is to see wild animals, and elephant is the most preferred animal. The visitors like to see bears, leopards, birds as well. In 2000 the income from visitors including lodge fees was approximately {{USD}}468,629.<ref name=\"Buultjens\" /> Due to security conditions revenue was lost.<ref name=\"Sunday Observer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/07/26/imp10.asp|title=Revamping national parks in a post-war setting|last=Prematunge|first=Sajitha|date=26 July 2009|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=17 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605233821/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2009/07/26/imp10.asp|archivedate=5 June 2011}}</ref> The Yala National Park has been susceptible to terrorist attacks. On 17 October 2007 a group of [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam|LTTE]] cadres attacked an army detachment in Thalgasmankada in the park.<ref name=\"Sunday Observer 2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/21/fea02.asp|title=Not a feather in Tiger cap|date=21 October 2007|work=Sunday Observer|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123124048/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2007/10/21/fea02.asp|archivedate=23 January 2008}}</ref> The attack killed six [[Sri Lanka Army|army soldiers]] and another was caught up in a landmine explosion. On 11 July 2008 four people died in an attack launched by the LTTE.<ref name=\"Daily News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/07/12/sec01.asp|title=Tigers fire at bus killing four|last=Wijayapala|first=Ranil|author2=Yatawara, Daneshi|date=12 July 2008|work=Daily News|accessdate=18 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604213030/http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/07/12/sec01.asp|archivedate=4 June 2011}}</ref> The cadres opened fire at a bus carrying pilgrims to [[Kataragama]]. Since the end of the civil war, May 2009, no violence has occurred in Yala area also and it is fully safe for visitors; this was also the main factor in opening blocks III and V for tourists.\n\nFrom January to June in 2008, 9,078 local tourists and 7,532 foreigners have visited Yala. For the same period of time in 2009 the arrivals have risen to 18,031 locals and foreigners to 10,439. Accordingly, the revenue increased to Rs. 27 million ({{USD}}235,000) in 2009 from Rs. 16.6 million ({{USD}}154,000) in 2008. The visitors are allowed to see the wild animals from 5.30 am to 6.30 pm.<ref name=\"Senaratna 2009\" /> Due to [[drought]]s the park used to be closed to tourists from 1 September, to 15 October annually; however in 2009 and 2010 the closure was skipped and lakes filled with water bowsers for drinking water for the animals, a future strategy on drought handling is not yet clear.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.yalasrilanka.lk Official website for Yala National Park]\n* [https://www.attractionsinsrilanka.com/travel-directory/yala-national-park/ Yala National Park bungalows]\n\n{{commonscat-inline|Yala National Park}}\n{{National Parks of Sri Lanka}}\n\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:National parks of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1900]]\n[[Category:Protected areas in Southern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Protected areas in Uva Province]]\n", "name_user": "2402:4000:2080:8f0f:d95c:6780:ee0:1fbb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yala_National_Park"}
{"title_page": "AdChoices", "text_new": "'''AdChoices''' is a self-regulatory program for online interest-based advertising that exists in the United States, Canada and across Europe. The program calls for advertising companies to establish and enforce responsible privacy practices for interest-based advertising, aimed to give consumers enhanced transparency and control. Companies adhere to a set of principles that are enforced by accountability programs.\n\n\"Interest-based advertising\" (also known as \"online behavioural advertising\" or \"behavioral targeting\") selectively displays ads based on browsing history, primarily using cookies, to users most likely to identify with and respond to the ad's specific content. The AdChoices icon is shown automatically by companies part of the self-regulatory program, and is meant to indicate to consumers when interest-based advertising data is being collected or used. By clicking on the icon (which is usually found in the top right corner of an online advertisement), a consumer can learn more about the ad or a website's collection practices, and be provided with the ability to opt-out of such targeting.\n\nAlthough it is possible to opt out of interest-based advertising through the AdChoices program(s), opting out does not block advertisements nor prevent tracking of web browsing history by use of other ways (e.g. Flash cookies). The US and Canadian AdChoices programs require that participating companies not use Flash cookies or similar locally shared objects for online interest-based advertising purposes.\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2009, the Federal Trade Commission began looking into internet advertising platforms and suggested that the industry develop guidelines for self-regulation. The American Association of Advertising Agencies, the Association of National Advertisers (ANA), the American Advertising Federation (AAF), the Direct Marketing Association (DMA), the Interactive Advertising Bureau (IAB), the Better Business Bureau (BBB), and the Network Advertising Initiative (NAI) joined together to form the Self-Regulatory Program for Online Behavioral Advertising. The alliance managing the program was called the '''Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA)'''. The DAA's AdChoices program was launched in October 2010.\n\nIn July 2013, additional principles were launched by the DAA to address interest-based data collected from smartphones and tablets. To give consumers a choice mechanism for that environment, in February 2015, the DAA officially launched AppChoices, an opt-out app for mobile devices.\n\nIn September 2013, the Canadian version of the AdChoices program was launched by the Digital Advertising Alliance of Canada (DAAC),  composed of a similar set of marketing and communications trade associations as in the US, to address the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada (OPC)'s guidelines for online behavioural advertising. The AdChoices program can be implemented in a manner consistent with existing Canadian privacy laws and the OPC's guidelines for online interest-based advertising.\n\n==Participants==\n\nThe AdChoices self-regulatory programs have over 200 participants.<ref name=participants>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/participating/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in the US|publisher = Your AdChoices - how interest based advertising finds you|accessdate = August 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=participantsCAN>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/participating-companies/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in Canada|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=participantsEU>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaa.eu/participating-companies/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in Europe|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> Participants include [[AOL]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://adinfo.aol.com/|title=Ad Choices: Why Did I Get This Ad?|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref> [[AT&T]], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], [[Comcast]], [[Conde Nast]], [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]], [[Facebook]],<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.facebook.com/help/568137493302217|title=How can I adjust how ads are targeted to me based on my activity off of Facebook?|publisher=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> [[General Motors]], [[Google Inc.]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/adsense/troubleshooter/1631343?hl=en|title=About Google Ads|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-revamps-labels-on-ads-to-comply-with-industry-effort-69424|title=Goodbye \"Ads By Google\" & Hello \"AdChoices\" As Google's Backs Industry Label Effort|last=Parker|first=Pamela|date=March 22, 2011|publisher=[[Search Engine Land]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Microsoft]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://choice.microsoft.com/en-ca/opt-out|title=About Our Ads|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref> [[Procter & Gamble]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pg.com/en_US/privacy/en_na/oba_notice.shtml|title=About Interest-Based Advertising|publisher=[[Procter & Gamble]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Taboola]], [[Yahoo!]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://info.yahoo.com/privacy/us/yahoo/relevantads.html|title=Why This Ad?|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> and many others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/participating/|title=Companies Using the Your AdChoices Icon|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> \n\nLists of Canadian and European program participants are found on their official websites.<ref name=\"participantsCAN\"/><ref name=\"participantsEU\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\nA study conducted by Parks Associates and discussed in [[AdAge]] found that three years after the introduction of the AdChoices icon, most consumers were unaware of it, and in fact, awareness had grown only from 5% in 2011 to 6% in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/article/privacy-and-regulation/study-consumers-adchoices-privacy-icon/291374/|title = Study: Consumers Don't Know What AdChoices Privacy Icon Is. After Three Years Just 6% Awareness Of the Industry's Opt-Out Program|date = January 29, 2014|accessdate = January 20, 2015|last = Kaye|first = Kate|publisher = [[AdAge]]}}</ref>  According to a [[TRUSTe]] survey from 2015: \"However, research also showed that awareness of the AdChoices icon, part of the Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA) Self-Regulatory Program for OBA [online behavioral ads, or interest-based ads] jumped to 37% \u2013 a significant increase from 21% the previous year. This program provides users with more control over their online ad experience with the option to opt-out of personal targeting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truste.com/about-truste/press-room/68-us-smartphone-users-concerned-activity-tracked-use-targeted-ads/|title = 68% of US Smartphone Users Concerned About Having Their Activity Tracked for Use in Targeted Ads = February 20, 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, in 10 of 13 European countries surveyed by [[TRUSTe]] and the European Interactive Digital Advertising Alliance in December 2015, at least 1 in 4 consumers who are aware of the icon say they have clicked on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truste.com/about-truste/press-room/growing-awareness-oba-icon/|title = New Research Shows Growing Awareness of the OBA Icon, and Understanding of this EU Industry Initiative to Give Control Over Targeted Advertising Choices = December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.youradchoices.com/ YourAdChoices.com (US)]\n* [http://youradchoices.ca YourAdChoices.ca (CAN)]\n* [http://www.youronlinechoices.eu YourOnlineChoices.eu (EUR)]\n* [http://www.youronlinechoices.com/uk YourOnlineChoices.com/uk (UK)]\n\n[[Category:Online advertising]]\n[[Category:Advertising regulation]]\n[[Category:Self-regulation]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=June 2016}}'''[[AdChoices]]''' is a [[Self-regulatory organization|self-regulatory program]] for [[online advertising|online interest-based advertising]] that exists in the United States, Canada and across Europe. The program calls for [[advertising companies]] to establish and enforce responsible [[internet privacy|privacy practices]] for [[interest-based advertising]], aimed to give consumers enhanced transparency and control. Companies adhere to a set of principles<ref name=officialUSprinciples>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/principles/|title = The DAA AdChoices Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialCANprinciples>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/the-principles/|title = The DAAC AdChoices Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialEUprinciples>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaa.eu/european-principles/|title = The EDAA AdChoices Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> that are enforced by accountability programs.<ref name=officialUSaccountability>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/enforcement/|title = Enforcement of the Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialCANaccountability>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/accountability/|title = Enforcement of the Canadian AdChoices Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialEUaccountability>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaa.eu/certification-process/trust-seal/|title = Enforcement of the European AdChoices Principles|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Interest-based advertising\" (also known as \"online behavioural advertising\" or \"[[behavioral targeting]]\") selectively displays ads based on browsing history, primarily using [[HTTP cookie|cookies]], to users most likely to identify with and respond to the ad's specific content. The AdChoices icon is shown automatically by companies part of the self-regulatory program, and is meant to indicate to consumers when interest-based advertising data is being collected or used. By clicking on the icon (which is usually found in the top right corner of an online advertisement), a consumer can learn more about the ad or a website's collection practices, and be provided with the ability to opt-out of such targeting.\n\nAlthough it is possible to opt out of interest-based advertising through the AdChoices program(s),<ref name=officialUSoptout>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/choices/|title = US Opt-Out Tool|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialCANoptout>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/choices/|title = Canadian Opt-Out Tool|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialUKoptout>{{cite web|url=http://www.youronlinechoices.com/uk/your-ad-choices/|title = UK Opt-Out Tool|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=officialEUoptout>{{cite web|url=http://www.youronlinechoices.com/|title = Other EU Opt-Out Tools|publisher = Available once country is selected|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> opting out does not block advertisements nor prevent tracking of web browsing history by use of other ways (e.g. [[Local shared object|Flash cookies]]). The US and Canadian AdChoices programs require that participating companies not use Flash cookies or similar locally shared objects for online interest-based advertising purposes.<ref name=officialCanadian-faq>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/faq/#flash-cookies|title = Does the consumer opt-out page give me choices about the use of Flash cookies for online interest-based advertising?|accessdate = June 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2009, the [[Federal Trade Commission]] began looking into internet advertising platforms and suggested that the industry develop guidelines for self-regulation. The [[American Association of Advertising Agencies]], the [[Association of National Advertisers]] (ANA), the [[American Advertising Federation]] (AAF), the [[Direct Marketing Association (United States)|Direct Marketing Association]] (DMA), the [[Interactive Advertising Bureau]] (IAB), the [[Better Business Bureau]] (BBB), and the [[Network Advertising Initiative]] (NAI) joined together to form the Self-Regulatory Program for Online Behavioral Advertising. The alliance managing the program was called the '''Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA)'''. The DAA's AdChoices program was launched in October 2010.<ref name=all-about-adchoices>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/blog/daa-celebrates-its-first-anniversary|title = DAA Celebrates its First Anniversary|date = Oct 25, 2011|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, additional principles were launched by the DAA to address interest-based data collected from smartphones and tablets.<ref name=officialUSmobileprinciples>{{cite web|url = http://www.aboutads.info/DAA_Mobile_Guidance.pdf/|title = Application of Self-Regulatory Principles to the Mobile Environment|accessdate = June 6, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161219050027/http://www.aboutads.info/DAA_Mobile_Guidance.pdf|archive-date = December 19, 2016|url-status = dead|df = mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/technology/want-opt-out-targeted-mobile-ads-theres-app-148509|title = Want to Opt Out of Targeted Mobile Ads? There's an App for That. Meets forthcoming DAA mobile privacy standards|last = Bachman|first = Katy|date = April 11, 2013|accessdate = January 21, 2015}}</ref> To give consumers a choice mechanism for that environment, in February 2015, the DAA officially launched AppChoices,<ref name=appchoices>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/appchoices/|title = AppChoices|date = Oct 25, 2011|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=appchoiceslaunch>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/blog/daa%E2%80%99s-new-mobile-choice-tools-journey-not-destination/|title = About the launch of AppChoices|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> an opt-out app for mobile devices.\n\nIn September 2013, the Canadian version of the AdChoices program was launched by the [[Digital Advertising Alliance of Canada (DAAC)]],  composed of a similar set of marketing and communications trade associations<ref name=aboutthedaac>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/about-the-daac/|title = About the DAAC|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> as in the US, to address the [[Privacy Commissioner of Canada|Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada (OPC)]]'s guidelines for online behavioural advertising.<ref name=opcguidelines>{{cite web|url=https://www.priv.gc.ca/information/guide/2011/gl_ba_1112_e.asp|title= Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada's Guidelines on Privacy and Online Behavioural Advertising|date = June 1, 2015}}</ref> The AdChoices program can be implemented in a manner consistent with existing Canadian privacy laws and the OPC's guidelines for online interest-based advertising.\n\n==Participants==\n\nThe AdChoices self-regulatory programs have over 200 participants.<ref name=participants>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/participating/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in the US|publisher = Your AdChoices - how interest based advertising finds you|accessdate = August 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=participantsCAN>{{cite web|url=http://youradchoices.ca/participating-companies/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in Canada|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref name=participantsEU>{{cite web|url=http://www.edaa.eu/participating-companies/|title = Companies using the AdChoices icon in Europe|accessdate = June 6, 2016}}</ref> Participants include [[AOL]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://adinfo.aol.com/|title=Ad Choices: Why Did I Get This Ad?|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref> [[AT&T]], [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]], [[Comcast]], [[Conde Nast]], [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]], [[Facebook]],<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.facebook.com/help/568137493302217|title=How can I adjust how ads are targeted to me based on my activity off of Facebook?|publisher=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> [[General Motors]], [[Google Inc.]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://support.google.com/adsense/troubleshooter/1631343?hl=en|title=About Google Ads|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://searchengineland.com/google-revamps-labels-on-ads-to-comply-with-industry-effort-69424|title=Goodbye \"Ads By Google\" & Hello \"AdChoices\" As Google's Backs Industry Label Effort|last=Parker|first=Pamela|date=March 22, 2011|publisher=[[Search Engine Land]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Microsoft]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://choice.microsoft.com/en-ca/opt-out|title=About Our Ads|accessdate=June 6, 2016}}</ref> [[Procter & Gamble]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pg.com/en_US/privacy/en_na/oba_notice.shtml|title=About Interest-Based Advertising|publisher=[[Procter & Gamble]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Taboola]], [[Yahoo!]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://info.yahoo.com/privacy/us/yahoo/relevantads.html|title=Why This Ad?|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> and many others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutads.info/participating/|title=Companies Using the Your AdChoices Icon|accessdate=January 20, 2015}}</ref> \n\nLists of Canadian and European program participants are found on their official websites.<ref name=\"participantsCAN\"/><ref name=\"participantsEU\"/>\n\n==Reception==\n\nA study conducted by Parks Associates and discussed in [[AdAge]] found that three years after the introduction of the AdChoices icon, most consumers were unaware of it, and in fact, awareness had grown only from 5% in 2011 to 6% in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/article/privacy-and-regulation/study-consumers-adchoices-privacy-icon/291374/|title = Study: Consumers Don't Know What AdChoices Privacy Icon Is. After Three Years Just 6% Awareness Of the Industry's Opt-Out Program|date = January 29, 2014|accessdate = January 20, 2015|last = Kaye|first = Kate|publisher = [[AdAge]]}}</ref>  According to a [[TRUSTe]] survey from 2015: \"However, research also showed that awareness of the AdChoices icon, part of the Digital Advertising Alliance (DAA) Self-Regulatory Program for OBA [online behavioral ads, or interest-based ads] jumped to 37% \u2013 a significant increase from 21% the previous year. This program provides users with more control over their online ad experience with the option to opt-out of personal targeting.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truste.com/about-truste/press-room/68-us-smartphone-users-concerned-activity-tracked-use-targeted-ads/|title = 68% of US Smartphone Users Concerned About Having Their Activity Tracked for Use in Targeted Ads = February 20, 2015}}</ref> Furthermore, in 10 of 13 European countries surveyed by [[TRUSTe]] and the European Interactive Digital Advertising Alliance in December 2015, at least 1 in 4 consumers who are aware of the icon say they have clicked on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truste.com/about-truste/press-room/growing-awareness-oba-icon/|title = New Research Shows Growing Awareness of the OBA Icon, and Understanding of this EU Industry Initiative to Give Control Over Targeted Advertising Choices = December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.youradchoices.com/ YourAdChoices.com (US)]\n* [http://youradchoices.ca YourAdChoices.ca (CAN)]\n* [http://www.youronlinechoices.eu YourOnlineChoices.eu (EUR)]\n* [http://www.youronlinechoices.com/uk YourOnlineChoices.com/uk (UK)]\n\n[[Category:Online advertising]]\n[[Category:Advertising regulation]]\n[[Category:Self-regulation]]\n", "name_user": "184.101.36.111", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AdChoices"}
{"title_page": "Classmate Stationery", "text_new": "{{advert|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Classmate\n| logo = ITC_Classmate_logo.png\n| type = \n| foundation = {{Start date|2003}}\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Kolkata, India]]\n| area_served = [[India]]\n| parent = [[ITC Limited]]\n| founder = \n| key_people = Shailendra Tyagi <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n| industry = [[Consumer goods]]\n| products = [[Notebook]]s<br>[[Pen]]s<br>[[Pencil]]s<br>Math instruments<br>[[Eraser]]s<br>Pencil sharpeners<br>Art stationery\n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.classmatestationery.com}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| native_name = \n| romanized_name = \n| trading_name = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n}}\n\n'''Classmate''' is an [[India]]n brand of student stationery products. [[ITC Limited]] (formerly Indian Tobacco Company) launched its Classmate brand in 2003 with the notebooks category. Subsequently, Classmate added pens, pencils, mechanical pencils and geometry boxes to its portfolio.\n\n== Products ==\nClassmate products include notebooks, [[pen]]s, [[pencil]]s, [[mechanical pencil]]s, [[diary|diaries]], mathematical drawing instruments, scholastics,  [[eraser]]s, sharpeners and scales and art stationery products.\n\n=== Notebooks ===\nClassmate notebooks consist of many variants including notebooks, long books, practical books, drawing books and reminder pads, with a theme on the cover and related information inside.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/itc-targetsschoolbag/382928/|title=ITC targets the schoolbag|date=2010-01-18|publisher=[[Business Standard]]}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerate11\">{{cite web |url=http://sify.com/finance/itc-to-grow-office-stationery-business-on-green-plank-news-corporate-jihkt6jibjg.html |title=ITC to grow office stationery business on green plank |date=2009-08-07 |publisher=sify.com}}</ref>\n\nITC Classmate notebooks use ozone-treated, elemental chlorine free paper, leading to higher paper quality and shelf life.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Anil Mascarenhas|title=Chand Das, Chief Executive, ITC-Education & Stationery Products Business|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/research-leader-speak/chand-das-chief-executive-itc-education-and-stationery-products-business-20500172_1.html|publisher=India Infoline}}</ref>\n\n=== Pens ===\nClassmate offers fountain pens, gel pens, roller pens and ball pens.<ref>{{cite web|title=ITC Classmate Pens|url=http://classmatestationery.com/products/?category=pens|website=Classmate Stationery}}</ref>\n\n=== Pencils ===\nClassmate's range of pencils includes wooden and mechanical pencils. Variants of wooden pencils include HB Bonded Lead, HB Jet Black, Carbon Black, 2B Trilobe and Rubber Tipped.\n\nThese pencils come with different features, clicking mechanisms, and grips.\n\n=== Art stationery products ===\nThe Colour Crew range of art materials includes wax crayons, plastic crayons, oil pastels and sketch pens.\n\n=== Mathematical instruments ===\nClassmate has several types of drawing instruments available.<ref name=\"autogenerated5\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story.html?sid=26023_Yuvraj+Singh+and+Soha+Ali+Khan+come+together+to+promote+ITCs+Classmate |title=Yuvraj Singh and Soha Ali Khan come together to promote ITC's Classmate |date=2010-01-13 |publisher= afaqs}}</ref>\n\n== Initiatives ==\n\n=== Classmate Ideas for India challenge ===\nClassmate launched a program called ''Classmate Ideas for India challenge''.<ref>[http://www.classmateideasforindia.com/ Classmate Ideas for India challenge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100904145757/http://www.classmateideasforindia.com/ |date=2010-09-04 }}</ref> This was a part of the company's centenary initiative.<ref name=\"autogenerated6\">{{cite web |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/cons-products/tobacco/ITC-Leading-Multi-business-conglomerate-turns-100/articleshow/6423526.cms?curpg=2 |title=ITC: Leading Multi-business conglomerate turns 100 |date=2010-08-24 |publisher=[[The Economic Times]]}}</ref> The nationwide program would invite ideas of the youth who have the potential to transform India. Classmate Ideas for India challenge plans to reach out to 2.5 million students across 30 cities, 500 schools and 200 colleges across the country.<ref name=\"autogenerated7\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2010/08/24/stories/2010082451200200.htm |title=ITC launches Classmate Ideas challenge |date=2010-08-23 |publisher=[[Business Line]]}}</ref> The CII-ITC Centre of Excellence for Sustainable Development, [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]] India, the Tony Blair Faith Foundation, Janaagraha and the Akshaya Patra Foundation among others are the program partners for the event.<ref name=\"autogenerated13\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afaqs.com/media/story.html?sid=28264_ITC+announces+Classmate+Ideas+for+India+Challenge |title=\nITC announces Classmate Ideas for India Challenge |date=2010-09-15 |publisher=afaqs}}</ref> The program will encourage the finalists with an internship with relevant program partners, besides cash prizes and other rewards. Additionally, the top five winners would be sent to a one-week international study tour.<ref name=\"autogenerated10\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/Markets/News/ITCs-Classmate-announces-Classmate-Ideas-for-India-Challenge/4913283067 |title=ITC\u2019s Classmate announces Classmate Ideas for India Challenge |date=2010-08-23 |publisher=India Infoline}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated12\">{{cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloids/ideas-india-432 |title=Ideas for India |date=2010-09-07 |publisher=Deccan Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n=== Discussions ===\nITC Classmate hosted a discussion on the subject titled \"Principal, Parents and Children: Building a Relationship of Mutuality\".<ref name=\"autogenerated\">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070313/asp/calcutta/story_7509444.asp |title=Bridging the gap |date=2007-03-13 |publisher= The Telegraph}}</ref> The panelists agreed on the need for greater student involvement in what they are taught, as well as the method of imparting education.\n\n=== Corporate social responsibility ===\nEvery Classmate notebook carries ITC's [[Corporate Social Responsibility]] message on its back. For every four Classmate notebooks purchased, ITC contributes {{INR}}1 to its social development initiative that supports, among other projects (including development of tobacco plantations to increase cigarette production), primary education.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2006/apr/12spec.htm|title=How ITC's filling up schoolbags|date=2006-04-12|publisher=rediff.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Classmate Young Authors Contest ===\nThe Classmate Young Authors Contest 2004 (CYAC 2004) was initiated by ITC Limited to provide a platform for budding writers among students to showcase their talent and an opportunity to develop it through interaction with some of the country's leading literary icons.<ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story.html?sid=10146_Eventus+Integrated+wins+business+worth+Rs+10+crore |title=Eventus Integrated wins business worth Rs 10 crore |date=2004-10-25 |publisher=afaqs}}</ref>\n\n=== Classmate Spell Bee ===\nClassmate Spellbee has completed nine seasons so far{{when|date=November 2018}} and is considered India's largest spelling competition. It aims to bring the best spellers together from every part of the nation, focusing on honing the spelling skills of Indian students in a fun and educational way.<ref>{{cite news|title=Season 8 of India\u2019s Largest Spelling Competition, Classmate Spell Bee is Here!|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/article/companies/season-8-of-indias-largest-spelling-competition-classmate-spell-bee-is-here/197193/|publisher=The Financial Express|date=January 18, 2016}}</ref> The last season winner received a cash prize of 2 lakh along with a sponsored trip to Washington DC, USA, to witness the Scripps National Spelling Bee 2015 with a parent.\n\n=== Classmate Art Academy ===\nThis first took off in 2015. Classmate launched a new initiative - Classmate Art Academy to promote its latest range of art products. The certificate training program brought together art teachers from top schools of New Delhi under one roof, to provide them with a platform to learn new skills. The property was executed by Victor Tango. Classmate recognizes the advantages of nurturing artistic pursuits in the all-round development of a child and aims at providing them with the right tools. The exciting range of Classmate Colour Crew products consist of Sketch Pens, Wax Crayons and Oil Pastels, designed to ensure that the uniqueness of each child shines through in the most colourful way.\n\n=== WWF-India and ITC Ltd. promoting responsible forestry ===\nThis first took off in 2009. ITC Classmate was  the first Indian company to join the Global Forest and Trade Network (GFTN).<ref name=\"autogenerated14\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwfindia.org/about_wwf/enablers/conservation_alliances/wwf_work_with/itc/|title= ITC Classmate|publisher= [[World Wide Fund for Nature]]|access-date= 2013-09-12|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131105112157/http://www.wwfindia.org/about_wwf/enablers/conservation_alliances/wwf_work_with/itc/|archive-date= 2013-11-05|url-status= dead}}</ref> Paperkraft Premium Business Paper  is a product of [[ITC Limited]] and is the country's greenest paper mill. ITC contributes towards saving the environment: through ozone treatment and ECF technology to eliminate toxicity in the industrial effluents released by them into the ecosystem, and in a large scale through reforestation and water conservation by planting 8 trees for every tree used, which has greened over 1 lakh hectares since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paperkraft Premium Business Paper lets you exercise your power to \"Go Green\"|url=http://www.itcportal.com/businesses/fmcg/education-and-stationery-products/paperkraft/go-green.aspx|website=ITC Portal}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http:/www.classmatestationery.com}} of Classmate Stationery\n* [http://www.itcportal.com/ ITC]\n\n{{ITC}}\n\n[[Category: Indian brands]]\n[[Category: Notebooks]]\n[[Category: Pens]]\n[[Category: Writing implements]]\n[[Category: Pencils]]\n[[Category: Companies based in Kolkata]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Classmate\n| logo = ITC_Classmate_logo.png\n| type = \n| foundation = {{Start date|2003}}\n| location_city = \n| location_country = [[Kolkata, India]]\n| area_served = [[India]]\n| parent = [[ITC Limited]]\n| founder = \n| key_people = Shailendra Tyagi <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n| industry = [[Consumer goods]]\n| products = [[Notebook]]s<br>[[Pen]]s<br>[[Pencil]]s<br>Math instruments<br>[[Eraser]]s<br>Pencil sharpeners<br>Art stationery\n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.classmatestationery.com}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| native_name = \n| romanized_name = \n| trading_name = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n}}\n\n'''Classmate''' is an [[India]]n brand of student stationery products. [[ITC Limited]] (formerly Indian Tobacco Company) launched its Classmate brand in 2003 with the notebooks category. Subsequently, Classmate added pens, pencils, mechanical pencils and geometry boxes to its portfolio.\n\n== Products ==\nClassmate products include notebooks, [[pen]]s, [[pencil]]s, [[mechanical pencil]]s, [[diary|diaries]], mathematical drawing instruments, scholastics,  [[eraser]]s, sharpeners and scales and art stationery products.\n\n=== Notebooks ===\nClassmate notebooks consist of many variants including notebooks, long books, practical books, drawing books and reminder pads, with a theme on the cover and 