{"title_page": "Cavalry scout", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name= Cavalry scout\n| image= ArmyCAVBranchPlaque.gif\n| caption=Cavalry branch plaque\n| dates= 17 November 1775\u2013present\n| country= United States\n| allegiance= United States of America\n| branch= [[United States Army]]\n| type= Main [[Armor Corps]] Element\n| role= Reconnaissance, security, assault\n| command_structure=\n| garrison=\n| garrison_label=\n| nickname=\n| patron= Saint George\n| motto=\n| colors=\n| colors_label=\n| march=\n| mascot=\n| equipment=\n| equipment_label=\n| battles=\n| anniversaries=\n| decorations=\n| battle_honours=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1=\n| commander1_label=\n| commander2=\n| commander2_label=\n| commander3=\n| commander3_label=\n| notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol=[[File:CavalryBC.gif]]\n| identification_symbol_label=Branch insignia\n| identification_symbol_2=\n| identification_symbol_2_label=\n| identification_symbol_3=\n| identification_symbol_3_label=\n| identification_symbol_4=\n| identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n\nThe '''Cavalry Scout''' or bronies is the job title used to refer to someone who has achieved the [[List of United States Army careers|military occupational specialty]] of 19D Armored Reconnaissance Specialist in the [[Combat Arms]] branch of the [[United States Army]]. As with all enlisted soldiers in the U.S. Cavalry, the person holding the Scout specialization will still be referred to as a [[Trooper (rank)|\u201dTrooper\u201d]], the traditional colloquialism denoted in the Cavalry's [[Order of the Spur]].\n\nCavalry Scouts use their special training to obtain, distribute, and share vital combat and battlefield information on the enemy and on [[combat]] circumstances and environmental conditions. The Cavalry Scout is also known as the \"eyes and ears\" of the Army.\n\n==Role==\nThe job of a Cavalry Scout is to operate as one of the first personnel in an area.\n\nCavalry Scouts gather information on the enemy by dismounted and/or mounted [[reconnaissance]] patrols. Cavalry Scouts engage the enemy with anti-armor weapons and scout vehicles in the field, track and report enemy movement and activities, and will direct the employment of various weapon systems onto the enemy.\n\nTheir specialized skills enable them to  assist with observation and listening posts, perform and help with [[navigation]], and help secure and transport [[ammunition]]. The Cavalry Scout leads, serves, or assists as a member of a scout crew, [[squad]], section, or [[platoon]] in reconnaissance, [[security]], and other [[combat]] operations.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Major Duties by Skill Level==\n'''Skill Level I''' (E1 [[Private (rank)|Private]] - E4 [[Specialist (rank)|Specialist/Corporal]])\n\n*Performs duties as crewmember, operates, and performs operator maintenance on scout vehicles: Cavalry Fighting Vehicle ([[M3 Bradley]] CFV), [[HMMWV]] (Humvee), [[M1127 Reconnaissance Vehicle]] (Stryker), crew-served weapons, anti-armor weapons, and communications equipment.\n*Loads, clears, and fires individual and crew-served weapons.\n*Engages enemy armor with anti-armor weapons.\n*Operates and performs operator maintenance on wheeled vehicles.\n*Assists in the recovery of wheeled and tracked vehicles. Secures, prepares, and stows ammunition on scout vehicles.\n*Performs mounted and dismounted navigation.\n*Serves as member of observation and listening post.\n*Gathers and reports information on terrain features and enemy strength, disposition, and equipment.\n*Applies principles of escape and evasion.\n*Collects data for the classification of routes, fords, tunnels, and bridges.\n*Performs dismounted patrols.\n*Employs principles of cover and concealment and camouflage.\n*Assists with construction of light field fortifications, laying and removal of mines, and emplacing demolitions.\n*Requests and adjusts indirect fire.\n\n'''Skill Level II''' (E5 [[Sergeant]])\n\n*Supervises scout vehicle crew.\n*Supervises operator maintenance of tracked and wheeled scout vehicles and individual and crew-served weapons.\n*Selects, organizes, and supervises operation of observation and listening posts.\n*Supervises scout vehicle recovery operations.\n*Trains scout vehicle crew.\n*Supervises request, receipt, storage, and issue of ammunition.\n*Leads scout vehicle crew and assists in leading scout squad.\n*Serves as gunner, on CFV, HMMWV, and M1127 Stryker RV.\n*May also serve as an Operations Assistant at brigade or squadron level.\n\n'''Skill Level III''' (E6 [[Staff Sergeant]])\n\n*Supervises scout sections and squads.\n*Directs tactical deployment of section and squads in combat.\n*Supervises maintenance of assigned vehicles and equipment.\n*Collects, reports and evaluates accuracy of intelligence information.\n*Directs reconnaissance of fording sites, tunnels, and bridges.\n*Directs route / area / zone reconnaissance at section level.\n*Coordinates action of vehicles with platoon and supporting elements.\n*Evaluates terrain, selected routes, assembly areas, firing positions, and positions for combat operations.\n*Identifies, selects targets, and issues fire commands.\n*Supervises construction of hasty fortifications.\n*Supervises section and squad resupply of class I, III, and V.\n*Trains scout section.\n*Coordinates requirements for organizational maintenance.\n*Conducts scout section drills.\n*Calls for, observes, and adjusts indirect fires.\n*May also serve as an Operations Assistant in the squadron/battalion or higher level staffs and as Operations NCO at troop level.\n\n'''Skill Level IV''' (E7 [[Sergeant First Class]])\n\n*Assists the commander or operations officer in planning, organizing, directing, supervising, training, coordinating, and reporting activities of the scout or armored cavalry platoon and staff sections.\n*Directs distribution of fire in combat.\n*Supervises platoon maintenance activities.\n*Collects, evaluates, and assists in interpretation and dissemination of combat information.\n*Directs platoon tactical movement, platoon security operations (screening), and platoon route/area/zone reconnaissance.\n*Supervises the employment of OPSEC measures.\n*Coordinates the evacuation of casualties.\n*Coordinates and conducts platoon resupply.\n*Requests and adjusts aerial fires.\n*May also serve as an Assistant Operations NCO at battalion or higher level.\n\n==Uniform==\nCavalry Scouts wear the ACU, or [[Army Combat Uniform]]. The standard camouflage pattern issued is the OCP ([[Operation Enduring Freedom|OEF]]) Camouflage Pattern, commonly referred to as [[Multicam]]. Two unique articles, the stetson hat as well as spurs, can be worn during special events or when directed by the chain of command. Cavalry Scouts are permitted to wear the [[Cavalry Stetson|Cavalry Stetson Hat]] with the Dress Uniforms during formal unit functions. The Stetson is traditionally accompanied by wearing the spurs which are earned when the unit conducts a \"Spur Ride.\"\n[[Order of the Spur|Cavalry Spurs]] can be earned by all Cavalry Scouts. Spurs may be worn on bloused combat boots with the dress uniforms and the duty uniform. The generally accepted Cavalry Spurs are the simplified Prince of Wales spurs (spurs without the [[rowel]], or star-shaped 'wheel' on the back).{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nA Scout is authorized to wear [[silver]] spurs if he has completed a Spur Ride, a rigorous series of physical and mental tasks/events designed to test the scout's military skills, military bearing, physical [[endurance]], mental fortitude, teamwork, ability to act under pressure and exhaustion, and ability to think and improvise quickly. The spur ride was similar to the Infantry's [[Expert Infantryman Badge]] in that only a scout could earn them. That tradition has since changed from the mid to late 1990s and now anyone serving in a Cavalry unit, CA or CSS can earn them. The Spur Ride rarely lasts more than three days (sometimes as little as one very long day and night), primarily due to U.S. Army regulations against hazing traditions. In short, it once was a \"gut\" check or a \"smoke\" session but it has changed with the times but some units still practice some of the older traditions when it comes to earning the spurs. The exact details of a Spur Ride varies according to the traditions of the particular Cavalry Squadron.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nA Scout who has previously earned his silver spurs and then serves in combat is eligible for [[brass]] or [[gold]] combat spurs. Scouts who have directly been involved in combat are often awarded combat spurs in lieu of the normally prerequisite silver spurs.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe Certificate awarded to Order of the Spur inductees, while honored by Cavalrymen everywhere, is not a document that is authorized for inclusion in a soldier's permanent official military file. Regardless, induction into the Order of the Spur is for life, and once awarded is recognized no matter which duty station the Cavalry Scout is assigned to.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nAlthough awarding of the Cavalry Spurs is often reserved for Cavalry troopers only, a deserving soldier or foreign military member who has provided great service (often in combat) to the Cavalry Squadron may be awarded Spurs.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe spurs and stetson are not authorized and are not official headgear or award. They are part of the esprit de corps that lives within the Cav.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Qualifications==\nPhysical demands rating and qualifications for initial award of military occupational specialty; the job is available to female personnel. Cavalry scouts must possess the following qualifications:\n\n*Physical Demands Rating = Very heavy\n*Physical profile (The [[PULHES Factor]]) = 111121 or better\n*Correctable vision of 20/20 in one eye and 20/100 in other eye\n*Normal color vision\n*A minimum score, of 87 in aptitude area CO ([[ASVAB]]/GT score)\n*Formal training (completion of military occupational specialty I 19D course conducted under the auspices of the U.S. Army Armor School) mandatory\n*Highest rank an individual may be reclassified into military occupational specialty 19D is rank SPC\n\n==Additional skill identifiers==\n*6B - Reconnaissance and Surveillance Leaders Course\n*D3 - Bradley Fighting Vehicle System\n*E9 - M901 (ITV) Gunner/Crew Training.\n*F7 - Pathfinder\n*J3 - Bradley Fighting Vehicle Master Gunner\n*P5 - Master Fitness Trainer\n*2C - [[FGM-148 Javelin|Javelin]] Gunnery\n*2S - Battle Staff Operations (skill level 3 and above)\n*4A - Reclassification Train\n*2B - Air Assault\n*B4 - Sniper (can attend training but will not be awarded ASI of B4)\n*R4 - [[Stryker]] Armored Vehicle Operator\n*R7 - Graduate of ARC (Army Reconnaissance Course)  All graduates of the Army Reconnaissance Course that are recommended by the Armor Proponent will be awarded the \u201cPersonnel Only\u201d SI/ASI R7 in coordination with the Branch Manager for that CMF.\n*R8 - Airborne Cavalry Sheridan Armour Tank **disbanded\n\n== Skill qualification identifiers ==\n*3 - Advisor\n*P - Parachutist\n*Q - Equal Opportunity Adviser\n*8 - Instructor\n*X - Drill Sergeant\n*V - Airborne Ranger\n*G - Ranger\n*4 - Recruiter\n*D - SHARP Representative\n\n===Training and School information===\nAll Cavalry Scouts attend OSUT (One Station Unit Training) at [[Fort Benning]] in Georgia. The first phase, roughly 9 weeks, is basic military training. The second phase, roughly 7 weeks long, focuses on becoming a Scout for a total of 16 weeks. The U.S. Army is currently testing and considering extending training to a 22-week OSUT course. During these final weeks the future Cavalry Scouts are trained by Instructors as well as their Drill Sergeants.\n\nThe OSUT training was moved from [[Fort Knox]], Kentucky, to Fort Benning, Georgia, in 2011.\n\nTraining is broken into color-coded phases, during which recruits gain increasing freedom, based on the recommendations of their drill Sergeants. Training requires good physical and mental condition, and is mostly hands-on, in the field.<ref name=\"U.S. Army Cavalry Scout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goarmy.com/careers-and-jobs/browse-career-and-job-categories/combat/cavalry-scout.html |title=Cavalry Scout (19D) |publisher=goarmy.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Cavalry Scouts==\n* [[Ty Carter]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Clinton Romesha]], Medal of Honor recipient\n* [[Elvis Presley]]<ref>https://www.elvis.com.au/presley/elvis-and-the-us-army.shtml</ref>\n* [[Kenneth Preston]], 13th [[Sergeant Major of the Army]]\n* [[Michael S. Tucker]], former Commanding General of the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n* [[Larry D. Wyche]], former Commanding General of [[Combined Arms Support Command]]\n* [[John W. Troxell]]<ref>https://dod.defense.gov/About/Biographies/Biography-View/article/633862/command-sergeant-major-john-wayne-troxell/</ref>, 3rd [[Senior Enlisted Advisor to the Chairman]] of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cavalry of the United States}}\n*[http://www.goarmy.com/JobDetail.do?id=39 Goarmy.com]\n*[http://usmilitary.about.com/od/enlistedjobs/a/19d.htm About.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040818103123/http://www.us-army-info.com/pages/mos/armor/19d.html Us-army-info.com]\n*Information derived from Army Pamphlet 611-21\n\n{{US Army MOS}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:United States Army job titles]]\n[[Category:Cavalry]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name= Cavalry scout\n| image= ArmyCAVBranchPlaque.gif\n| caption=Cavalry branch plaque\n| dates= 17 November 1775\u2013present\n| country= United States\n| allegiance= United States of America\n| branch= [[United States Army]]\n| type= Main [[Armor Corps]] Element\n| role= Reconnaissance, security, assault\n| command_structure=\n| garrison=\n| garrison_label=\n| nickname=\n| patron= Saint George\n| motto=\n| colors=\n| colors_label=\n| march=\n| mascot=\n| equipment=\n| equipment_label=\n| battles=\n| anniversaries=\n| decorations=\n| battle_honours=\n<!-- Commanders -->\n| commander1=\n| commander1_label=\n| commander2=\n| commander2_label=\n| commander3=\n| commander3_label=\n| notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol=[[File:CavalryBC.gif]]\n| identification_symbol_label=Branch insignia\n| identification_symbol_2=\n| identification_symbol_2_label=\n| identification_symbol_3=\n| identification_symbol_3_label=\n| identification_symbol_4=\n| identification_symbol_4_label=\n}}\n\nThe '''Cavalry Scout''' is the job title used to refer to someone who has achieved the [[List of United States Army careers|military occupational specialty]] of 19D Armored Reconnaissance Specialist in the [[Combat Arms]] branch of the [[United States Army]]. As with all enlisted soldiers in the U.S. Cavalry, the person holding the Scout specialization will still be referred to as a [[Trooper (rank)|\u201dTrooper\u201d]], the traditional colloquialism denoted in the Cavalry's [[Order of the Spur]].\n\nCavalry Scouts use their special training to obtain, distribute, and share vital combat and battlefield information on the enemy and on [[combat]] circumstances and environmental conditions. The Cavalry Scout is also known as the \"eyes and ears\" of the Army.\n\n==Role==\nThe job of a Cavalry Scout is to operate as one of the first personnel in an area.\n\nCavalry Scouts gather information on the enemy by dismounted and/or mounted [[reconnaissance]] patrols. Cavalry Scouts engage the enemy with anti-armor weapons and scout vehicles in the field, track and report enemy movement and activities, and will direct the employment of various weapon systems onto the enemy.\n\nTheir specialized skills enable them to  assist with observation and listening posts, perform and help with [[navigation]], and help secure and transport [[ammunition]]. The Cavalry Scout leads, serves, or assists as a member of a scout crew, [[squad]], section, or [[platoon]] in reconnaissance, [[security]], and other [[combat]] operations.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Major Duties by Skill Level==\n'''Skill Level I''' (E1 [[Private (rank)|Private]] - E4 [[Specialist (rank)|Specialist/Corporal]])\n\n*Performs duties as crewmember, operates, and performs operator maintenance on scout vehicles: Cavalry Fighting Vehicle ([[M3 Bradley]] CFV), [[HMMWV]] (Humvee), [[M1127 Reconnaissance Vehicle]] (Stryker), crew-served weapons, anti-armor weapons, and communications equipment.\n*Loads, clears, and fires individual and crew-served weapons.\n*Engages enemy armor with anti-armor weapons.\n*Operates and performs operator maintenance on wheeled vehicles.\n*Assists in the recovery of wheeled and tracked vehicles. Secures, prepares, and stows ammunition on scout vehicles.\n*Performs mounted and dismounted navigation.\n*Serves as member of observation and listening post.\n*Gathers and reports information on terrain features and enemy strength, disposition, and equipment.\n*Applies principles of escape and evasion.\n*Collects data for the classification of routes, fords, tunnels, and bridges.\n*Performs dismounted patrols.\n*Employs principles of cover and concealment and camouflage.\n*Assists with construction of light field fortifications, laying and removal of mines, and emplacing demolitions.\n*Requests and adjusts indirect fire.\n\n'''Skill Level II''' (E5 [[Sergeant]])\n\n*Supervises scout vehicle crew.\n*Supervises operator maintenance of tracked and wheeled scout vehicles and individual and crew-served weapons.\n*Selects, organizes, and supervises operation of observation and listening posts.\n*Supervises scout vehicle recovery operations.\n*Trains scout vehicle crew.\n*Supervises request, receipt, storage, and issue of ammunition.\n*Leads scout vehicle crew and assists in leading scout squad.\n*Serves as gunner, on CFV, HMMWV, and M1127 Stryker RV.\n*May also serve as an Operations Assistant at brigade or squadron level.\n\n'''Skill Level III''' (E6 [[Staff Sergeant]])\n\n*Supervises scout sections and squads.\n*Directs tactical deployment of section and squads in combat.\n*Supervises maintenance of assigned vehicles and equipment.\n*Collects, reports and evaluates accuracy of intelligence information.\n*Directs reconnaissance of fording sites, tunnels, and bridges.\n*Directs route / area / zone reconnaissance at section level.\n*Coordinates action of vehicles with platoon and supporting elements.\n*Evaluates terrain, selected routes, assembly areas, firing positions, and positions for combat operations.\n*Identifies, selects targets, and issues fire commands.\n*Supervises construction of hasty fortifications.\n*Supervises section and squad resupply of class I, III, and V.\n*Trains scout section.\n*Coordinates requirements for organizational maintenance.\n*Conducts scout section drills.\n*Calls for, observes, and adjusts indirect fires.\n*May also serve as an Operations Assistant in the squadron/battalion or higher level staffs and as Operations NCO at troop level.\n\n'''Skill Level IV''' (E7 [[Sergeant First Class]])\n\n*Assists the commander or operations officer in planning, organizing, directing, supervising, training, coordinating, and reporting activities of the scout or armored cavalry platoon and staff sections.\n*Directs distribution of fire in combat.\n*Supervises platoon maintenance activities.\n*Collects, evaluates, and assists in interpretation and dissemination of combat information.\n*Directs platoon tactical movement, platoon security operations (screening), and platoon route/area/zone reconnaissance.\n*Supervises the employment of OPSEC measures.\n*Coordinates the evacuation of casualties.\n*Coordinates and conducts platoon resupply.\n*Requests and adjusts aerial fires.\n*May also serve as an Assistant Operations NCO at battalion or higher level.\n\n==Uniform==\nCavalry Scouts wear the ACU, or [[Army Combat Uniform]]. The standard camouflage pattern issued is the OCP ([[Operation Enduring Freedom|OEF]]) Camouflage Pattern, commonly referred to as [[Multicam]]. Two unique articles, the stetson hat as well as spurs, can be worn during special events or when directed by the chain of command. Cavalry Scouts are permitted to wear the [[Cavalry Stetson|Cavalry Stetson Hat]] with the Dress Uniforms during formal unit functions. The Stetson is traditionally accompanied by wearing the spurs which are earned when the unit conducts a \"Spur Ride.\"\n[[Order of the Spur|Cavalry Spurs]] can be earned by all Cavalry Scouts. Spurs may be worn on bloused combat boots with the dress uniforms and the duty uniform. The generally accepted Cavalry Spurs are the simplified Prince of Wales spurs (spurs without the [[rowel]], or star-shaped 'wheel' on the back).{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nA Scout is authorized to wear [[silver]] spurs if he has completed a Spur Ride, a rigorous series of physical and mental tasks/events designed to test the scout's military skills, military bearing, physical [[endurance]], mental fortitude, teamwork, ability to act under pressure and exhaustion, and ability to think and improvise quickly. The spur ride was similar to the Infantry's [[Expert Infantryman Badge]] in that only a scout could earn them. That tradition has since changed from the mid to late 1990s and now anyone serving in a Cavalry unit, CA or CSS can earn them. The Spur Ride rarely lasts more than three days (sometimes as little as one very long day and night), primarily due to U.S. Army regulations against hazing traditions. In short, it once was a \"gut\" check or a \"smoke\" session but it has changed with the times but some units still practice some of the older traditions when it comes to earning the spurs. The exact details of a Spur Ride varies according to the traditions of the particular Cavalry Squadron.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nA Scout who has previously earned his silver spurs and then serves in combat is eligible for [[brass]] or [[gold]] combat spurs. Scouts who have directly been involved in combat are often awarded combat spurs in lieu of the normally prerequisite silver spurs.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe Certificate awarded to Order of the Spur inductees, while honored by Cavalrymen everywhere, is not a document that is authorized for inclusion in a soldier's permanent official military file. Regardless, induction into the Order of the Spur is for life, and once awarded is recognized no matter which duty station the Cavalry Scout is assigned to.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nAlthough awarding of the Cavalry Spurs is often reserved for Cavalry troopers only, a deserving soldier or foreign military member who has provided great service (often in combat) to the Cavalry Squadron may be awarded Spurs.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe spurs and stetson are not authorized and are not official headgear or award. They are part of the esprit de corps that lives within the Cav.{{Citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\n==Qualifications==\nPhysical demands rating and qualifications for initial award of military occupational specialty; the job is available to female personnel. Cavalry scouts must possess the following qualifications:\n\n*Physical Demands Rating = Very heavy\n*Physical profile (The [[PULHES Factor]]) = 111121 or better\n*Correctable vision of 20/20 in one eye and 20/100 in other eye\n*Normal color vision\n*A minimum score, of 87 in aptitude area CO ([[ASVAB]]/GT score)\n*Formal training (completion of military occupational specialty I 19D course conducted under the auspices of the U.S. Army Armor School) mandatory\n*Highest rank an individual may be reclassified into military occupational specialty 19D is rank SPC\n\n==Additional skill identifiers==\n*6B - Reconnaissance and Surveillance Leaders Course\n*D3 - Bradley Fighting Vehicle System\n*E9 - M901 (ITV) Gunner/Crew Training.\n*F7 - Pathfinder\n*J3 - Bradley Fighting Vehicle Master Gunner\n*P5 - Master Fitness Trainer\n*2C - [[FGM-148 Javelin|Javelin]] Gunnery\n*2S - Battle Staff Operations (skill level 3 and above)\n*4A - Reclassification Train\n*2B - Air Assault\n*B4 - Sniper (can attend training but will not be awarded ASI of B4)\n*R4 - [[Stryker]] Armored Vehicle Operator\n*R7 - Graduate of ARC (Army Reconnaissance Course)  All graduates of the Army Reconnaissance Course that are recommended by the Armor Proponent will be awarded the \u201cPersonnel Only\u201d SI/ASI R7 in coordination with the Branch Manager for that CMF.\n*R8 - Airborne Cavalry Sheridan Armour Tank **disbanded\n\n== Skill qualification identifiers ==\n*3 - Advisor\n*P - Parachutist\n*Q - Equal Opportunity Adviser\n*8 - Instructor\n*X - Drill Sergeant\n*V - Airborne Ranger\n*G - Ranger\n*4 - Recruiter\n*D - SHARP Representative\n\n===Training and School information===\nAll Cavalry Scouts attend OSUT (One Station Unit Training) at [[Fort Benning]] in Georgia. The first phase, roughly 9 weeks, is basic military training. The second phase, roughly 7 weeks long, focuses on becoming a Scout for a total of 16 weeks. The U.S. Army is currently testing and considering extending training to a 22-week OSUT course. During these final weeks the future Cavalry Scouts are trained by Instructors as well as their Drill Sergeants.\n\nThe OSUT training was moved from [[Fort Knox]], Kentucky, to Fort Benning, Georgia, in 2011.\n\nTraining is broken into color-coded phases, during which recruits gain increasing freedom, based on the recommendations of their drill Sergeants. Training requires good physical and mental condition, and is mostly hands-on, in the field.<ref name=\"U.S. Army Cavalry Scout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goarmy.com/careers-and-jobs/browse-career-and-job-categories/combat/cavalry-scout.html |title=Cavalry Scout (19D) |publisher=goarmy.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Cavalry Scouts==\n* [[Ty Carter]], [[Medal of Honor]] recipient\n* [[Clinton Romesha]], Medal of Honor recipient\n* [[Elvis Presley]]<ref>https://www.elvis.com.au/presley/elvis-and-the-us-army.shtml</ref>\n* [[Kenneth Preston]], 13th [[Sergeant Major of the Army]]\n* [[Michael S. Tucker]], former Commanding General of the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n* [[Larry D. Wyche]], former Commanding General of [[Combined Arms Support Command]]\n* [[John W. Troxell]]<ref>https://dod.defense.gov/About/Biographies/Biography-View/article/633862/command-sergeant-major-john-wayne-troxell/</ref>, 3rd [[Senior Enlisted Advisor to the Chairman]] of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Cavalry of the United States}}\n*[http://www.goarmy.com/JobDetail.do?id=39 Goarmy.com]\n*[http://usmilitary.about.com/od/enlistedjobs/a/19d.htm About.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040818103123/http://www.us-army-info.com/pages/mos/armor/19d.html Us-army-info.com]\n*Information derived from Army Pamphlet 611-21\n\n{{US Army MOS}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:United States Army job titles]]\n[[Category:Cavalry]]\n", "name_user": "75.137.250.175", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavalry_scout"}
{"title_page": "British Rail Class 158", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox DMU\n| background = #0033cc; color:white\n| name = British Rail Class 158 ''Express Sprinter''\n|image = Crewe_-_Keolis-Amey_158830_Chester_service.JPG\n|caption = [[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]] 158830 at {{stnlnk|Crewe}} in 2020\n|interiorimage = Train Interior (14099118197).jpg\n|imagesize = 300px\n|interiorcaption = Refurbished [[Arriva Trains Wales]] interior in 2014\n| manufacturer = [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]<ref name=\"angeldata\">{{cite web\n| url=http://www.angeltrains.co.uk/Products-Services/Regional-Passenger-Trains/6\n| title=Data Sheets - Regional Passenger Trains: 158 -  BREL Express Sprinter\n| publisher=Angel Trains\n| accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n| factory = [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]]<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| family = [[Sprinter (train)|Sprinter]]\n| yearconstruction = 1989\u20141992<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| numberbuilt = 182 sets (30 converted to 159s)\n| replaced = {{ubl|locomotive-hauled passenger train|[[List of British Rail diesel multiple unit classes#First generation|First generation DMUs]]}}\n| numberservice = 170 sets\n| formation = 2 or 3 cars per set\n| service = 17 September 1990 \u2013 present\n| operator = [[East Midlands Railway]]<br>[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]<ref name=\"FGWFleetpage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.firstgreatwestern.co.uk/Content.aspx?id=57 |accessdate=29 April 2010 |title=First Great Western: Regional Train Fleet |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020021646/http://www.firstgreatwestern.co.uk/Content.aspx?id=57 |archivedate=20 October 2011  }}</ref><br>[[Abellio ScotRail]]<br>[[Northern Trains (train operating company)|Northern Trains]]<br>[[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]]<br>[[Transport for Wales Rail|Transport for Wales]]<!-- NOT State Railway of Thailand -->\n| refurbishment =\n| carbody =  [[Welding|Welded]] [[aluminium]]<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| carlength =  {{convert|23.21|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"FGWFleetpage\" />\n| width =  {{convert|2.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| height =\n| weight =  {{convert|37.8|t|ST LT|abbr=on}} or <br /> {{convert|38.5|t|ST LT|abbr=on}} per car<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| capacity = '''Northern:'''<br>138, 142 (158/0 & 158/9) or 207 (158/0) seats per unit<ref>{{cite web|title=THE NORTHERN INTERIM FRANCHISE AGREEMENT|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/329103/northern-interim-franchise-agreement.pdf|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n| maxspeed =  {{convert|90|mph|abbr=on|0}}<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| multipleworking = Classes 14x, 15x and {{brc|170}}<ref name=TRC1 />\n| gauge =  {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}} \n| traction =  [[Diesel Multiple Unit|DMU]]<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| engine = one per car <br> [[Cummins UK|Cummins]] NTA855R1 <br>''(158701 - 158814 and 158901 - 158910)'' <br>[[Perkins Engines|Perkins]] 2006-TWH ''(158815 - 158862)'' <br>Cummins NTA855R3 <br>''(158863 - 158872)''<br>''numbers as built''<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| enginetype = [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]\n| poweroutput      = Cummins: {{convert|350|hp|kW|abbr=on}}<br>Perkins {{convert|350|hp|kW|abbr=on}}<br>Cummins: {{convert|400|hp|kW|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| transmission =  [[Voith]] T211rz or T211rzz [[Hydrokinetic transmission|hydraulic]] <br>[[Gmeinder]] GM 190 final drive <br>2 axles driven per car<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| brakes =  [[Railway air brake|Pneumatic]], [[Railway disc brake|Disc]]<ref name=\"angeldata\" />\n| safety =  [[Automatic Warning System#British Rail AWS|AWS]], [[Train Protection & Warning System|TPWS]], [[European Train Control System|ETCS]]<ref name=ERTMS>{{cite web|url=http://www.europeanrailwayreview.com/rail-industry-news/pioneering-rail-technology-gets-tested-in-wales |author=Network Rail |title=ERTMS gets tested in Wales |accessdate=16 September 2010 |date=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n| coupling = [[BSI coupling|BSI]]<ref name=TRC1 >{{cite web|url=http://www.rssb.co.uk/RGS/Pages/MECHANICALANDELECTRICALCOUPLINGINDEX.aspx |title=Mechanical And Electrical Coupling Index |accessdate=20 December 2010 |publisher=Rail Safety and Standards Board |url-status=dead \n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221005408/http://www.rssb.co.uk/RGS/Pages/MECHANICALANDELECTRICALCOUPLINGINDEX.aspx |archivedate=21 December 2013  }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''British Rail Class 158''' ''[[Sprinter (train)|Express Sprinter]]'' is a [[diesel multiple-unit]] (or DMU), built specifically for [[British Rail]] between 1989 and 1992 by [[British Rail Engineering Limited]] (BREL) at its [[Derby Litchurch Lane Works]]. They were built to replace many locomotive-hauled passenger trains, and allowed cascading of existing Sprinter units to replace elderly [[List of British Rail diesel multiple unit classes#First generation|'heritage' DMUs.]]<ref name=\"CBOL\">Garratt, Colin. ''The Complete Book of Locomotives''. Anness Publishing Ltd. 1997, 2010. p. 134-5. {{ISBN|1844770222}}</ref> The [[British Rail Class 159|Class 159]] DMUs are almost identical to the Class 158s, having been converted from Class 158 to Class 159 in two batches to operate express services from [[West of England Main Line|London Waterloo to the West of England]].<ref name=\"SWTFleetpage\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southwesttrains.co.uk/our-trains.aspx#65962 |accessdate=18 September 2010 |title=Our Trains |publisher=South West Trains |year=2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221125507/http://www.southwesttrains.co.uk/our-trains.aspx#65962 |archive-date=21 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.porterbrook.com/images/pic_library/pdf/Class%20159.pdf | title = Class 159 | publisher = Porterbrook | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110726123030/http://www.porterbrook.com/images/pic_library/pdf/Class%20159.pdf | archivedate = 26 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n===Variants===\nA total of 182 units were built.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=British Rail in the 1980s and 1990s: Diesel Locomotives and DMUs|last=Barclay|first=Kenny|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2017|isbn=9781445670065|location=|pages=}}</ref> The majority were built as two-car sets. 17 units were built as three-car units; eight of these units have since had the centre car transferred to different units of the class, whilst another eight have been upgraded to be [[British Rail Class 159|Class 159s]].<ref name=\"SWTFleetpage\" /> The final ten units were built specifically for [[West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive|West Yorkshire PTE ''Metro'']] services around [[Leeds]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebeautyoftransport.com/2017/03/01/local-heroes-pte-mainline-rail-visual-identities-1970-1994/|title=Local Heroes (PTE mainline rail visual identities 1970-1994)|date=1 March 2017|work=The Beauty of Transport|access-date=8 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Passenger facilities and performance===\n[[File:158784 Interior.jpg|left|thumb|The interior of a [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern Rail]] refurbished Class 158 (First Refurbishment)|alt=]]\nWhen introduced, [[British Rail]] described the Class 158s as bringing \"new standards of comfort and quality to rail travel on [[Regional Railways]]' key long-distance cross-country routes\".<ref name=\"BRB_Promo\">British Rail Central Advertising Services: \"Your New Train is Here\", January 1991.</ref>\n\nAs built, interiors were described as fully carpeted, with \"panoramic\" windows and a variety of seats arranged both airline-style and in bays of four around tables. Unlike previous members of the Sprinter family, such as the [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]] ''SuperSprinter'', the Class 158s featured air conditioning, an on-board payphone, power-operated interior doors, a toilet in each carriage, and provision for a refreshment trolley service. Despite an increased top speed of {{convert|90|mph|abbr=on|0}}, the units also promised a smoother, quieter ride than its predecessors.<ref name=\"BRB_Promo\" />\n\nThe Class 158s were expected to achieve {{convert|13500|mi|km}} of operation between major services and a range of up to {{convert|1600|mi|km}} from each refuelling.<ref name=\"BRB_Promo\" />\n\n===Technical problems===\nDespite the attention given to passenger facilities, the build and engineering technology of the Class 158s has caused some issues.<ref name=\"Scotsman\">{{Cite news\n| title = ScotRail launches \u00a32.2m bid to improve unreliable trains\n| newspaper = The Scotsman | location=Edinburgh\n| url = http://news.scotsman.com/topstories/ScotRail-launches-22m-bid-to.2347382.jp\n| accessdate = 28 May 2010| date=29 July 2002 |last=Dalton | first = Alastair\n}}</ref> As a lightweight unit and the first members of the [[Sprinter (train)|''Sprinter'']] family to use [[disc brakes]], [[Slippery rail|autumn leaf mulch]] built up on wheel rims and prevented the units from correctly operating signalling [[track circuit]]s.<ref>[http://members.madasafish.com/~dysgraphyk/156/class156_mods.htm#tca Class Modifications - 156 Super-Sprinter section ''Track Circuit Actuators (TCA)'']</ref> Though later solved by installing scrubbing blocks to clean the wheels, temporary solutions were sought in October 1992, with some units split and formed into hybrid units with [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]] coaches,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Misformed Sets - 156 Super-Sprinter - Trans-Pennine Hybrids\n| work = Metro-Cammell Class 156 Super-Sprinter\n| url = http://members.madasafish.com/~dysgraphyk/156/class156_misformed.htm#TP158\n| accessdate = 15 June 2008\n}}\n</ref> as the latter had tread brakes which cleaned the wheels as a by-product of their operation.\n\nThe class has also suffered from unreliable air-conditioning systems<ref name=\"Scotsman\" /> since the outlawing of the [[Chlorofluorocarbon|CFC]] gases with which they were originally designed to work.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Environmental Report 2001\n| work = National Express Group\n| url = http://www.nationalexpressgroup.com/nx1/corporate/cr_reports/env2001/env2001.pdf\n| accessdate = 28 May 2010\n| url-status = dead\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101128233745/http://nationalexpressgroup.com/nx1/corporate/cr_reports/env2001/env2001.pdf\n| archivedate = 28 November 2010\n| df = dmy-all\n}}</ref> Following privatisation, many operators undertook to re-engineer or entirely replace such equipment.<ref>{{Cite journal| editor-first=Howard | editor-last=Johnston | year=2001 | title=The comprehensive guide to Britain's Railways, 4th ed. | publisher= EMAP Active | location=Peterborough | issn=1368-437X }}</ref> As a result, the systems in use and their effectiveness now vary across the fleet.\n\nThe lightweight aluminium body of the Class 158s leads to a good 'route availability' score,<ref name=\"angeldata\" /> meaning that it is able to operate in parts of Britain where heavier units cannot. However, the units were refused permission by [[Network Rail]] to operate on the [[Conwy Valley Line|Conwy Valley]] and [[Borderlands Line|Borderlands]] lines due to station dwell times and issues of platform clearance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/network%20code/vehicle%20change/current%20vehicle%20change%20proposals/class%20158/vc%20f2%202005%20class%20158%20atw%20lnw%20013/c%20rejection.pdf |title=Rejection of proposed Vehicle Change: Class 158 Blaenau Ffestiniog Branch |publisher=[[Network Rail]] |date=22 December 2005 |accessdate=25 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/network%20code/vehicle%20change/current%20vehicle%20change%20proposals/class%20158/vc%20f2%202005%20class%20158%20atw%20lnw%20014/c%20rejection.pdf |title=Rejection of proposed Vehicle Change: Class 158 Wrexham Central to Bidston |publisher=Network Rail |date=22 December 2005 |accessdate=25 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\n===British Rail===\n[[File:Class 158 DMU 158819 to Portsmouth, Bristol Temple Meads 27.2.1993. (9922352786).jpg|thumb|British Rail 158819 at {{stnlnk|Bristol Temple Meads}} in 1993]]\n[[ScotRail (British Rail)|ScotRail]] was the first part of British Rail to introduce the Class 158s to public service in September 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.madasafish.com/~dysgraphyk/156/class156_timeline.htm|title=156 - Time Line|website=members.madasafish.com|access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/executive-blocks-scotrail-plan-to-trade-away-most-unreliable-trains-1-656130|title=Executive blocks ScotRail plan to trade away most unreliable trains|access-date=8 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> These were employed on {{Stnlnk|Glasgow Queen Street}} to {{Stnlnk|Edinburgh Waverley}} services, as well as services to {{Stnlnk|Aberdeen}} and {{Stnlnk|Inverness}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-scotrail-logo-on-british-rail-class-158-express-sprinter-diesel-multiple-134364550.html|title=Stock Photo - ScotRail Logo on British Rail Class 158 Express Sprinter diesel multiple unit. Kyle of Lochalsh station, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland, United Kingdom|last=Limited|first=Alamy|website=Alamy|language=en|access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref> The Class 158s then went on to be deployed elsewhere in Britain, primarily in the Midlands, Northern England, Wales and the South West.<ref name=\"BRB_Promo\" />\n\nWith the majority of the fleet coming under the control of the [[Regional Railways]] division, the Class 158s became a mainstay of secondary express services between provincial towns and cities.  Examples included long-distance Trans-Pennine services in the north of England, as well as a range of upgraded regional services under the [[Alphaline]] brand in the Midlands, Wales and the South West.\n\nA small batch of units numbered 158747-158751 were used by [[InterCity (British Rail)|InterCity]] to supplement its core fleet on some cross-country services, mainly from the North West to Scotland, but also to Portsmouth. Units regularly appeared on off-peak workings between Birmingham and Manchester, and also on Sunday mornings between Birmingham and Doncaster.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n===Post privatisation===\nAfter the [[privatisation of British Rail]], the Class 158 fleet was divided among several franchises.\n\n====ScotRail====\n[[File:25.08.13 Glasgow Central 158.869 (9597856463).jpg|thumb|A [[First ScotRail]] class 158 at Glasgow Central in 2013]]\nThe first privatised incarnation of ScotRail inherited a 46-strong fleet which continued in service.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/scotrail-launches-163-2-2m-bid-to-improve-unreliable-trains-1-614525|title=ScotRail launches \u00a32.2m bid to improve unreliable trains|access-date=8 June 2018|language=en}}</ref> Following the introduction of newly built [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170]] Turbostar units on primary express services in 1999, the Class 158 fleet was reduced in number by six, with those remaining cascaded away to secondary routes such as the [[Far North Line]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/special-rail-carriages-plan-to-ease-bike-crowding-on-scottish-trains-1-4681973|title=Special rail carriages plan to ease bike crowding on Scottish trains|access-date=8 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, plans existed for part of the fleet to be swapped with [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156]] units operated by [[Central Trains]], as the latter were thought better suited to some of the short-distance routes now being operated by ScotRail's 158s.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.meaker.me.uk/Rail/Class/DMU-2/DMU-2.htm#Class156\n|title=2nd Generation Multiple Units\n|publisher=www.meaker.me.uk\n|accessdate=28 June 2010\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307010052/http://www.meaker.me.uk/Rail/Class/DMU-2/DMU-2.htm#Class156\n|archive-date=7 March 2012\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref> However, this failed to materialise and by the mid-2000s operations of the ScotRail 158s ranged from short hops (such as Glasgow Queen Street to {{Stnlnk|Anniesland}}) to rural lines and long-distance expresses, supplementing other express units. In 2010 these units started to appear at Glasgow Central station to run on the Glasgow Central to Edinburgh via Shotts line, and on to the Glasgow Central to Whifflet line. Some additional units have since been acquired from other operators to provide extra capacity.<ref>[http://www.therailwaycentre.com/Picture%20of%20the%20Day%20index/Old_POD_Mar2008.html Picture of the Day 11 March 2008], therailwaycentre.com.</ref><ref>[http://www.scot-rail.co.uk/page/Class+158+Relivery+Details Class 158 Relivery Details], scot-rail.co.uk (Enthusiast website).</ref>\n\nRefurbishment and reliverying has also taken place since privatisation. The original [[ScotRail (National Express)|ScotRail]] franchise applied its own livery to the Class 158s, followed by a further repaint by [[First ScotRail]] after it took control of the franchise. The fleet has now gained a permanent blue-and-white livery based on the Scottish [[Saltire]], after [[Transport Scotland]] announced in September 2008 that it was specifying a permanent livery for all Scottish trains, which would not be changed in the event of a change of franchisee.<ref>[http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/files/4952_transport_scotland_vista_lo_res.pdf \"Scotland's Railway\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406222700/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/files/4952_transport_scotland_vista_lo_res.pdf |date=6 April 2012 }}, Transport Scotland.</ref> Interiors have also seen attention on more than one occasion. The most recent refurbishment of 25 units involved repainting, new seating, extra luggage space and new customer information systems.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.concept-applications.com/case_study2.php | title=Railcare Springburn Class 158 Scotrail Internal refurbishment | publisher=Concept Applications | accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.railcare-uk.com/files/downloads/Class%20158%20Express.pdf | title=Renovation: Class 158 Express (DMU) | publisher=RailCare | accessdate=28 June 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715150727/http://www.railcare-uk.com/files/downloads/Class%20158%20Express.pdf | archivedate=15 July 2011 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/reports/corporate/j11465-04.htm | title=Delivery against our priorities: Improved connections | date=17 December 2009 | publisher=Transport Scotland | access-date=29 May 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303215610/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/reports/corporate/j11465-04.htm | archive-date=3 March 2010 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Toilet retention tanks were also fitted.\n\nIn 2018, the additional 8 units acquired by Scotrail from other TOCs were transferred to Northern in stages - the first two occurring in February 2018 and the remainder in December 2018.\n\nSeveral of the ScotRail units have had names attached - for example 158702 is named ''BBC Scotland - 75 Years'', 158707 is named ''Far North Line - 125th Anniversary'', 158715 is named ''Haymarket'' and 158720 is named ''Inverness and Nairn Railway - 150 Years''.\n<gallery>\nFile:Railway near Muir of Ord Golf Course - geograph.org.uk - 349212.jpg|National Express Group 158722 in 2004\nFile:158738 at Whifflet.jpg|First ScotRail 158738 in 2012\n</gallery>\n\n====Transport for Wales====\n[[File:Barmouth railway station MMB 06 158823.jpg|thumb|right|Unrefurbished [[Arriva Trains Wales]] (ATW) 158823 at {{rws|Barmouth}} in 2009. Class 158s are required on [[Cambrian Line]] services as they are the only TfW trains fitted with the [[ERTMS|ERTMS signalling]] used on the line.]]\n[[File:Crewe - Keolis-Amey 158830 Chester service.JPG|thumb|158830 at {{Stnlnk|Crewe}} in [[Transport for Wales Rail Services|Transport for Wales]] colours.]]\nIn the early days of privatisation, the Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' units were in regular use by [[Wales & West]] on its long-distance [[Alphaline]] services from South Wales to North-West England, North Wales, Cornwall and [[London Waterloo railway station|London Waterloo]], as well as on some [[Central Trains]] services to {{rws|Cardiff Central}} and along the [[Cambrian Line]].<ref>[http://www.railfaneurope.net/pix/gb/diesel/dmu/158/CT/pix.html#158mach.jpg Wales and Borders trains in 2002], railfaneurope.net picture gallery.</ref> Successor companies [[Wales & Borders]] (2001) and [[Arriva Trains Wales]] (2003) continued to use this type of unit on similar workings, with a total allocation of 40 units also allowing Cambrian Line services to become entirely Class 158-operated.<ref>[http://www.sarpa.info/pdf%20archive/sarpa20.pdf Newsletter No. 20], Shrewsbury to Aberystwyth Rail Passengers' Association, 2001.</ref> By the end of 2006, a total of 16 units (158815-158817 and 158842-158854) had returned to the leasing company<ref name=\"158FleetList\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thejunction.org.uk/flist_158.html|title= Fleet lists: Class 158| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205220049/http://www.thejunction.org.uk/flist_158.html |archive-date=5 February 2012 |publisher= thejunction.org.uk}}</ref> as Arriva gained exclusive use of the entire Class 175 ''Coradia'' fleet which had previously been shared with other train operators.\n\nThe remaining 24-strong Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' fleet became permanently based at a purpose-built depot in [[Machynlleth]] during 2007.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://railnews.co.uk/news/environment/2007/09/17-past-powers-arriva-future.html | title = Pioneering past powers Arriva's future | date = 17 September 2007 | newspaper = RailNews | location = Stevenage }}</ref> Despite initial problems in retro-fitting the necessary '[[glass cockpit]]'-style driver controls,<ref name=\"BBCglare\">{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_west/8687851.stm |title=Sun glare delays new train system |work=BBC News Online|date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> Arriva's Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' units became the first fleet in the UK to be equipped for regular use with the [[ETCS|ETCS Level 2]] signalling system.<ref name=ERTMS /><ref name=\"nwrailbbbertms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nwrail.org.uk/nw1005d.htm |title=North Wales Coast Railway Notice Board 24 May 2010 |date=24 May 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2010 |first=Charlie | last = Hulme}}</ref> Commercial operation under ETCS started on 28 March 2011.<ref name=\"rgz-2011-6-61\">{{Citation | author=Chris Jackson | title= Intelligent train management will cut costs | journal=[[Railway Gazette International]] | volume=166 | issue= 6 | year=2011 | pages= 60-64 | ISSN=0373-5346 }}</ref>\n\nAccordingly, the units operate all Cambrian Line services between Mid Wales and Birmingham, as well as supplementing the Class 175 ''Coradia'' units on other long-distance routes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/search/?q=arriva%20158%20holyhead|title=Search: arriva 158 holyhead|publisher=}}</ref> In 2009, Arriva also proposed using the fleet to provide a direct service between {{rws|Aberystwyth}} and London,<ref>{{cite press release | publisher = Arriva Trains Wales | date = 4 September 2009 | url = http://www.arrivatrainswales.co.uk/Templates/News.aspx?pageid=811 | title = Proposal for new direct Aberystwyth to London service submitted to the Office of Rail Regulation | access-date = 10 January 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110728133233/http://www.arrivatrainswales.co.uk/Templates/News.aspx?pageid=811 | archive-date = 28 July 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> although this proposal was later rejected by the Office of Rail Regulation.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/mid/8543836.stm| title = Aberystwyth to London direct rail route rejected | work = BBC News Online | location = London | date = 1 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nA complete refurbishment programme to provide the Class 158s with full 'as new' interiors took place between December 2010<ref>{{cite press release | url = http://wales.gov.uk/newsroom/transport/2010/100802arriva/?lang=en | publisher = Welsh Assembly Government | date = 2 August 2010 | title = Refurbishment of Arriva Trains Wales fleet announced | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120330105322/http://wales.gov.uk/newsroom/transport/2010/100802arriva/?lang=en | archivedate = 30 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/2010/08/02/taxpayers-to-pay-for-7-5m-trains-upgrade-55578-26976819/ | newspaper = Daily Post | location = Liverpool | date = 2 August 2010 | first = Eryl | last = Crump | title = Taxpayers to pay for \u00a37.5m trains upgrade }}</ref> and October 2012. Funded by the Welsh Assembly Government at a cost of \u00a37.5m, work completed included interior and exterior repainting, along with replacement of seating, wall coverings, carpets, lighting, luggage racks and toilet fittings. A passenger information system has been fitted, while selected seats gained at-seat power sockets for mobile phones and laptops.<ref>{{cite web|year=2010 |url=http://www.transportbusiness.net/content/view/702/2/ |publisher=Transport Business International |title=\u00a37.5m upgrade for Arriva Trains Wales |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724112405/http://www.transportbusiness.net/content/view/702/2/ |archivedate=24 July 2011  }}</ref>\n\nUntil this refurbishment, the fleet had seen only minor attention to its interior since a refit by Wales & West in the late 1990s (little more than the fabric on the older seats changed and CCTV fitted) as well as having been only partially repainted into Arriva colours externally. The door controls and exterior destination displays did start to be replaced before the major refurbishment. <ref name=\"158FleetList\" />\n\nWiFi was fitted in 2017, and Persons with Reduced Mobility modifications began in June 2018, with toilet retention tanks also being fitted. On 14 October 2018, these units transferred to [[Transport for Wales Rail Services|Transport for Wales]]. In February 2019, the first unit was seen in Transport for Wales colours. These are set to be replaced by 2023 alongside the rest of the [[Transport for Wales Rail Services|Transport for Wales]] fleet by a total of 77 [[British Rail Class 197|Class 197]] units. <ref>{{cite news |title=\u00a3800m fleet renewal plan for new Welsh franchise |url=https://www.railjournal.com/passenger/main-line/800m-fleet-renewal-plan-for-new-welsh-franchise/ |accessdate=2 April 2019 |work=International Railway Journal |publisher=Simmons-Boardman |date=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====East Midlands Railway====\n[[File:158854 Sheffield.jpg|thumb|right|A pair of East Midlands Trains Class 158s, led by No. 158854, at Sheffield]]\nThe Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' Units were introduced to the [[East Midlands]] by [[Regional Railways|Regional Railways Central]] to replace the [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156 ''SuperSprinter'']] on long-distance express services branded as [[Alphaline]], such as {{rws|Norwich}} to {{rws|Liverpool Lime Street}} via {{rws|Nottingham}}. Following privatisation, [[Central Trains]] operated these services but quickly procured a large fleet of [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170 ''Turbostar'']] units for such services and transferred the Class 158 fleet to secondary routes such as {{Stnlnk|Birmingham New Street}} to {{Stnlnk|Hereford}} and {{Stnlnk|Derby}} to {{Stnlnk|Matlock}}.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n[[East Midlands Trains]] (EMT) had a fleet of 25 units inherited from Central Trains, with some units transferred from [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|First Great Western]] and [[South West Trains]]. EMR's Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' units operate long-distance express services (such as Norwich to Liverpool)<ref name=\"MR201204p56\">{{cite news |title=Nottingham-Liverpool capacity boost: Four-cars on key inter-urban route |author=Miles, Tony |work=Modern Railways |date=April 2012 |location =Stamford |pages=56\u201358}}</ref> and secondary non-express workings such as Nottingham to {{rws|Skegness}}, Nottingham to Matlock and {{Stnlnk|Leicester}} to {{Stnlnk|Lincoln Central}}.\n\nThe hourly Norwich to Liverpool service has been criticised for overcrowding,<ref name=\"Rail 630\">{{Cite news |last=Clinnick |first=Richard |title=Class 158s set to relieve overcrowding for EMT |work=Rail |location =Peterborough |volume=630 |page=28 |date=4 November 2009}}</ref> especially between Liverpool and Nottingham. This resulted from the Department for Transport specifying two-coach units in the EMT franchise starting in November 2007. In the light of persistent and excessive overcrowding, with some passengers being left behind on occasions, the DfT eventually admitted that it had made a mistake.<ref name=\"MR201204p56\" /> Various cascades of other units enabled more Class 158 stock to be released for this route, and from the December 2011 timetable change the busiest services have been lengthened to four-coach trains between Liverpool and Nottingham, with units splitting and joining at Nottingham as necessary, two-coach trains being regarded as adequate between Nottingham and Norwich. Further services on this route were strengthened from December 2012.<ref name=\"MR201204p56\" />\n\nIn May 2015 158889 transferred to EMT from South West Trains on a 2-year loan. This allocation was then made permanent in August 2017 following Stagecoach's loss of the South Western franchise to [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]].\n\nAll units passed to [[East Midlands Railway]] on 18 August 2019 and run under the \u201cEMR Regional\u201d sub-brand. They are expected to be replaced by Class 170s on regional services in 2021/2022.\n\n====Great Western Railway====\n[[File:GWR 158956 02.jpg|thumb|right|Great Western Railway 158956 at {{rws|Bristol Temple Meads}} in July 2016]]\nThe [[Wales & West]] franchise (later [[Wessex Trains]]) originally operated twelve Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' units on long-distance services on the [[Wessex Main Line]]. These units were extended into three-coach formations with the acquisition of further units. Unlike the purpose-built three-car Class 158s and [[British Rail Class 159|Class 159]] units, the centre car was a Driving Motor with the cab locked out of use and an adapter to connect the different-sized gangways.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn 2006, [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|First Great Western]] (FGW) inherited the Wessex Trains fleet following the merger of the Great Western and Wessex franchises. FGW then swapped most of their former Wessex Trains Class 158s for former [[First TransPennine Express]] examples. This was so that FGW could have all Class 158 units that were owned by [[Porterbrook]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} During late 2007 and early 2008, the FGW Class 158 ''Express Sprinter'' fleet was refurbished. Improvements included: re-upholstery of seats, and repainting or replacement of interior fittings, alterations to interior lighting and total replacement of toilets. Additionally, the windows have been replaced with safer laminated glass and [[Halon systems|Halon]] fire extinguishers replaced with foam ones. At the same time, the units' engines were overhauled and the units repainted in FGW's own lilac and blue colours.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view//great-western-regional-refurbishment-underway.html |title=Great Western regional refurbishment underway |date=12 December 2007 |work=[[Railway Gazette International]] | location=London}}</ref>\n\nThe fleet is now used on long-distance services between [[Exeter St David's railway station|Exeter St Davids]] and [[Plymouth railway station|Plymouth]] / [[Penzance railway station|Penzance]], {{Stnlnk|Cardiff Central}} and [[Taunton railway station|Taunton]] / {{Stnlnk|Portsmouth Harbour}} and {{Stnlnk|Great Malvern}} / {{Stnlink|Worcester Shrub Hill}} and {{Stnlnk|Brighton}} / {{Stnlnk|Weymouth}}. They are now also used on the [[Tarka Line]] on services between [[Barnstaple railway station|Barnstaple]] and [[St James Park railway station|St James' Park]] replacing the [[British Rail Class 143|class 143 pacers]] which were running on the line. [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]] operates a total of 18 units, of which 6 are hybrids (units where one end coach is a driving coach from another unit of the same class tagged on to a 2 car unit), one is a purpose-built 3 car unit and the remaining 11 are two coach sets.<gallery>\nFile:Wessex Alphaline 158863.jpg|Wessex Trains 158863 in 2005\nFile:Hugh llewelyn 158 951 (6340205655).jpg|First Great Western 158951 in 2008\nFile:Bristol Temple Meads - GWR 158956 arriving from Bristol Parkway.JPG|Great Western Railway 158956 in 2016\nFile:Inside GWR 52748 (158956).JPG|Interior of a refurbished Great Western Railway Class 158.\n</gallery>\n\n====Northern Trains/TransPennine Express====\n[[File:158910 Interior.jpg|thumb|The interior of a Northern refurbished Class 158/9 (First Refurbishment)|alt=]]\n\nFollowing privatisation [[Arriva Trains Northern|Northern Spirit]] (later [[Arriva Trains Northern]], and subsequently [[Northern Rail (Serco-Abellio)|Northern Rail]] in 2004) was created from Regional Railways North East. Northern Spirit inherited a large fleet of Class 158 units, many of which were used on TransPennine Express services, the rest on [[West Yorkshire]] Metro-sponsored services. [[First North Western]] (descended from Regional Railways North West) had eight Class 158s, which were based at Newton Heath and used on various mid- to long-distance routes, which were transferred to Leeds Neville Hill depot at the start of the Northern rail franchise and are now exclusively used on former Arriva Trains Northern routes.  A number of 158s are currently sponsored by [[Merseytravel]] despite the fact that they do not go near Merseyside.  This sponsorship is to ensure that [[British Rail Class 156|Class 156s]] were cascaded from West Yorkshire to the busiest Merseyside services.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn 2006 First TransPennine Express started to replace its Class 158s with newer [[British Rail Class 185|Class 185 ''Desiro'']] and [[British Rail Class 170|Class 170 ''Turbostar'']] units.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://d3cez36w5wymxj.cloudfront.net/migrated/tpe_class_185_research_final.pdf |title=The Pennine Class 185 experience |pages=4-5}}</ref> The Class 158s were subsequently transferred to Northern Rail, Central Trains, South West Trains and First Great Western.\n\nAll units were passed to Northern Rail in April 2016. Northern has recently completed a refurbishment programme on the three-car Class 158 DMUs and is continuing to refurbish its fleet of two-car Class 158 DMUs.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} It and Abellio ScotRail operate the largest fleet of Class 158 units.\n\nIn 2018, Northern acquired an additional 8 Class 158 units from Abellio Scotrail; the first few units transferring in February 2018 with the remainder in December 2018.\n\n====South West Trains/South Western Railway====\n[[File:Southampton Central - SWR 158887 Salisbury service.JPG|thumb|right|South Western Railway Class 158 at Southampton Central]]\nCurrently [[South Western Railway (train operating company)|South Western Railway]] operates Class 158s from {{Stnlnk|Exeter St Davids}} to [[London Waterloo railway station|Waterloo]] and on the Salisbury to {{Stnlnk|Romsey}} via {{Stnlnk|Southampton Central}} service.<ref name=\"SWTFleetpage\" /> South Western Railway also operates [[British Rail Class 159|Class 159]] units, converted from Class 158 units during the [[Network SouthEast]] years. One of the [[South West Trains]] units, number 158889, has been permanently transferred to sister Stagecoach company, [[East Midlands Trains]], and their original pair of 158s were transferred permanently to Abellio ScotRail. South Western Railway operates Class 158s 158880-888 and 890. 158885 was fitted with a ZF fuel saving transmission instead of the usual [[Voith]] T211rz or T211rzz hydraulic, but this was ultimately unsuccessful and the unit had reverted to the original arrangement by March 2017. Originally brought in to replace [[South West Trains]] class 170 fleet, SWT's class 158s saw a brief use on the former Reading to Brighton service, before the service was truncated at both ends within the new South Western franchise of 2007.\n\n====Virgin CrossCountry====\nPrior to the introduction of the [[British Rail Class 220|Class 220]]/[[British Rail Class 221|221 Virgin Voyagers]], [[Virgin CrossCountry]] operated a small number of Class 158s, numbers 158747-158751. These were used on Manchester Piccadilly/Liverpool Lime Street to Glasgow/Edinburgh services via the [[West Coast Main Line]]. One also did the Swindon-Stroud-Birmingham route. Most of these units are now operated by [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} <!--I don't have any references to support this last statement, but I have a photograph at home of 158747 in a Wessex Trains livery advertising 200 years of railways that I will upload. I presume the others in the batch have also been allocated to WX-->\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On 3 December 2005, unit 158856 was involved in an accident at {{rws|Elsenham}} in which two passengers were killed whilst crossing the line. The RAIB criticised the risk assessment at the crossing as inadequate.<ref name=BBC3472865>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/essex/3472865.stm |title=Inquiry into rail crossing deaths |work=BBC News Online |date=4 December 2005 |accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=RAIBElsenham>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/547c9062e5274a42900001d1/R232006_061211_Elsenham.pdf |title=Investigation into station pedestrian crossings (including pedestrian gates at highway level crossings); with reference to the fatal accident at Elsenham station on 3 December 2005 |publisher=Rail Accident Investigation Branch |accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 22 January 2010, unit 158701 was derailed at {{rws|Dingwall}} due to faulty points. One person sustained minor injuries.<ref name=RAIBDingwall>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/547c8ff3ed915d4c0d00017b/100930_B112010_Dingwall.pdf |title=Derailment at Dingwall, Scotland  22 January 2010 |publisher=Rail Accident Investigation Branch |accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 21 July 2013, unit 158774 was parked empty at {{rws|Norwich}} when it was run into by [[British Rail Class 156|156 402]]. Eight passengers were injured. The cause was driver error.<ref name=RAIBNorwich>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/410636/140501_R092014_Norwich.pdf |title=Passenger train collision at Norwich 21 July 2013 |publisher=Rail Accident Investigation Branch |accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n* On 1 April 2017, unit 158758 collided with the [[buffer stop]]s at {{rws|Preston}} at a speed of {{convert|6|mph|km/h|abbr=on|0}}. Fifteen people were injured. The cause was driver error.<ref name=RAIBPreston>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/620615/D102017_170621_Preston.pdf |title=Passenger train collision with buffer stop at Preston station, 1 April 2017 |publisher=Rail Accident Investigation Branch |accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Overseas sales==\n===State Railway of Thailand===\n[[File:2503class158.jpg|thumb|[[State Railway of Thailand ASR class]] at [[Bangkok railway station]] in 2013 after being refurbished]]\nIn 1990\u20131991, BREL built six 3-car [[State Railway of Thailand ASR class|ASR class]] units based on the Class 158 for [[State Railway of Thailand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voithturbo.de/media/g1610e-class2500.pdf|title=Voith|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=export158>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrewgrantham.co.uk/state-railway-of-thailand-class-158-a-like/ |title=Export Class 158 in Thailand| first=Andrew |last=Grantham}}</ref> These differ from the British units in being fitted to Thailand's [[narrow gauge railway|metre gauge]], featuring differently styled outer-end gangways, manually operated inward-opening hinged doors (as opposed to the British plug doors), reversible seating and additional air-conditioning. They originally retained the original white, blue and black 'Regional Railways Express' livery.<ref name=export158 /> All units of Class 158 of State Railway of Thailand were refurbished in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portal.rotfaithai.com/modules.php?name=Forums&file=viewtopic&t=3968&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=20|title=Sprinter refurbishment}}</ref> The refurbishment involved the repainting of the trains into a new livery and the lengthening of the trains to four coaches.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Current fleet==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Class\n!Operator\n!Number\n!Year built\n!Cars\n!Unit number\n|-\n!rowspan=9|158/0\n|[[Abellio ScotRail]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n| rowspan=\"11\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|1989&ndash;92\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|158701&ndash;736, 158738&ndash;741\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n| style